1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:17,000
This is Emily Crossby with Betty Carmen Robinson on December 8, 2015 in her home in Baltimore.

3
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:20,000
And we're here with the Civil Rights History Project,

4
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:27,000
co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

5
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:32,000
And also here is John Bishop and Kuhashanker.

6
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:34,000
And thank you very much.

7
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Oh, what's my pleasure.

8
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:40,000
And can you tell us when and where you were born and about your family?

9
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
Sure, I was born on January 8, 1939.

10
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:48,000
And I was born in New York City.

11
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:52,000
My father was a professor at maybe, I don't know, full professor.

12
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:58,000
And now that I know that I know assistant associate, whatever, I don't know what kind of professor he was,

13
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,000
but he was a professor of physics and chemistry at New York University.

14
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:06,000
And he had grown up on a farm.

15
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:12,000
So he got a college opportunity at Franklin Marshall College in Pennsylvania.

16
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
And then he went to NYU and got a PhD.

17
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:21,000
And that was like big for his family having, you know, actually his parents were

18
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:23,000
Pennsylvania, German.

19
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,000
They barely spoke English.

20
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:33,000
So for him that was big to be catapulted into this position.

21
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:37,000
And then my mother was born in New York City in a working class family.

22
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:42,000
Born in, I don't know if she was born in flushing, but New York City anyway.

23
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Her mother was the daughter of an Irish immigrant and her father was the son of German.

24
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:56,000
And she grew up, she was the first in her family to go to college.

25
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
She went to NYU also, which is where she met my dad.

26
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:02,000
And then I was born in 39.

27
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:05,000
My brother was born in 42.

28
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:10,000
And what else do you want to know about that?

29
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:12,000
What was your family like?

30
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
What was your growing up experience?

31
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:15,000
Oh, okay.

32
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:22,000
So my growing up experience, both my mother and father, this was like during World War II, right?

33
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:30,000
So my father moved, we moved to Cambridge, Massachusetts, and my father worked at MIT in the radiation lab,

34
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
which was the laboratory where the atomic bomb was being constructed.

35
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:42,000
And I don't think he knew what part in developing the bomb he was playing,

36
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:46,000
but he had something to do with radar.

37
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:49,000
And so we had moved to Cambridge.

38
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:56,000
My brother was, well, we were both, you know, preschool kindergarten age when we lived there.

39
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:00,000
And I can remember the air raids.

40
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:07,000
I can remember the blocking our, this is again World War II, I can remember the threat of war.

41
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:14,000
So blocking our, the light from our house with dark curtains or turning the lights off,

42
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:19,000
or when an air raid would happen hiding under the bed, I can remember all those things.

43
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:27,000
And I think that connected with my later anti-war sentiments, because as a kid when you live that trauma,

44
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:33,000
you're not conscious of what those feelings are, but later on it comes to the surface.

45
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
So there was that piece.

46
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Then we moved to back to New York, and we moved eventually by the time I was in second grade,

47
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:50,000
we moved to a suburb Pleasantville, New York, where there was a new laboratory that my father was working at.

48
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:58,000
He was kind of the chief scientist of a, it was called a general precision equipment, or general precision GPL.

49
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:05,000
It was called general precision labs first and became general precision equipment, and then it became something else after that.

50
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:11,000
But so it was in the era where these labs were consolidating and bigger companies were buying them.

51
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:27,000
But I can remember him coming home, tormented and upset and really angry and sometimes crying because of the competition and the cutthroat nature of the job that he had.

52
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:32,000
And the people around him, and he was a very collaborative type of person.

53
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:42,000
And as a scientist, I think he wanted that collaboration, but there was a lot of jealousy and there was a lot of back biting, and he was just tortured by all of that happening.

54
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:52,000
So I think that, and we'll jump forward ahead, you know, some of my feelings, like when my brother and I were in college,

55
00:04:52,000 --> 00:05:00,000
we talked about how we were not going to work in corporate America because of what we had seen my dad go through.

56
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:10,000
We were like absolutely no corporate America for us. And that was my brother too. He became a veterinarian, but never worked for a big corporate firm.

57
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:19,000
So that was kind of a key thing in my values formation, I think. And again, reflecting back, I don't know where the values that I got,

58
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:24,000
the progressive values that I got actually came from.

59
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:33,000
There's other pieces like my mother was very prejudiced and very, very anti-black, anti- Anybody of color.

60
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:41,000
And I would push back against that. I think on one level because she also was critical of every friend I ever had.

61
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:50,000
And those were white friends. So she would say, I don't like her, her parents are immigrants. And I would say, but wait a minute, your grandmother was an immigrant.

62
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Or she would say, I don't like this family because they're working class or when the first boyfriend I had was a son of a truck driver.

63
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:05,000
And I would be like, wait, there's a contradiction here. Like you grew up the daughter of a carpenter.

64
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:18,000
I mean, it just didn't compute to me. So the fact that she was prejudiced and then some other incidents that happened, which I can tell you, but I'll let you ask another question.

65
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:25,000
When you talk about your dad and the work being very competitive and how upsetting.

66
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:35,000
How does that work if he's in the lab? Is it competitive with other scientists or is there pressure on him because of competition between companies? Do you ever sense about that?

67
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:47,000
No, I think because it was called GPL, General Precision Labs, but it wasn't a laboratory per se. I mean, they were involved in the first television production. They were involved in a lot of different equipment.

68
00:06:47,000 --> 00:07:02,000
The competition was mostly from, if I can remember this well enough, from non-scientists who wanted to be in his position in the corporate structure. In other words, the corporate ladder.

69
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:16,000
He was given a particular role because of his knowledge. And his library, he had books all over his library, all these scientific magazines and every night he would be reading and pouring over all this kind of cutting-edge science.

70
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:22,000
Because this is the late 40s, right, where science is just blossoming, right?

71
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:33,000
But his work is more of a managerial. Yes, his work is exactly more managerial because of the knowledge that he has. So he's not really...

72
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:41,000
I mean, he is overseeing some of the scientific work, but it's not pure scientific.

73
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:48,000
And so he's feeling this competitiveness and this absolute backstabbing and that kind of thing.

74
00:07:48,000 --> 00:08:02,000
So it was kind of like this turmoil and this tension that he brought home almost every night and then it bled over to my mother and her anxieties about her life, having grown-up working class and being...

75
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:17,000
Both of them are feeling not accepted in their new class. In other words, they're both feeling very uncomfortable when they go to a party or when they host somebody at the house. They're like very, almost like having six thumbs.

76
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:26,000
And they don't talk about that, but you can tell that that's their discomfort. They never joined a country club. I think that would have been...

77
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Like, they didn't have the quote social graces that they thought was expected of them. I'm sure some of the other people were also going through the same thing, but because nobody talked about anything then, nobody shared any of their deepest feelings, you know.

78
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:50,000
Did you ever listen to this when you were young or is this sort of looking back and trying to make sense of what you did experience?

79
00:08:50,000 --> 00:09:05,000
It's partly looking back, but it's partly I can remember the tension around. I can remember my father's anguish and anxiety and anger. I can remember that very, very vividly, but I didn't know how to piece it together.

80
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:15,000
I didn't understand the class stuff until I got... until I was avasnic, probably, or in-snick. I don't know. I didn't really understand that.

81
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:23,000
I clearly didn't understand the racial prejudice. Like, when I was in high school, my brother and I worked at a YMCA camp.

82
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:33,000
And there was a black woman who was a vassar student, who was a counselor. Now, you have to understand my mother wanted me to go to one of the hot shot women's colleges.

83
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:41,000
And I was totally resistant to that. No, I'm not going to Smith vassar, Wellesley, Radcliffe. No, I'm not going there.

84
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:48,000
So I picked Skidmore, which was kind of up in those ranks, but it was like a lesser than school, right?

85
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:56,000
And of course, my shock when I got to Skidmore was my roommate brought in 30 pairs of shoes. And this is in 1956, right?

86
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:07,000
And I'm like, what is this? So I thought I was rejecting this upper class life at these other colleges and bumped right smack into it.

87
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:16,000
But anyway, vassar was one of the schools that my mother had wanted me to go to. And even look at, I refused to even go visit these schools.

88
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:25,000
So here we have an African American woman vassar student on the staff of the YMCA day camp.

89
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:30,000
My brother and I, because we're the brother sister team, we decide to host a party at our house.

90
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:37,000
So we host a party at our house. All the counselors come. We have a great time. Then everybody leaves. And then I'm looking for my mother.

91
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:48,000
And my mother is like, where is she? And my dad says, well, she's down the basement. She had a little room, a little room, like an office room where she did sewing and crafts and stuff.

92
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:58,000
So I go down there and she's in tears. And I'm like, well, what the heck is going on? And she's like, you will never live us down. You brought a nigger into the house.

93
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Well, the neighbors think. And I'm like, well, first, my first comment was, well, it's dark. Nobody saw. I mean, that was like the utilitarian way.

94
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:17,000
But the second thing is, wait a minute. This is a woman who we work with every day. She's a vassar student. Like, what objection could you have to that?

95
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:36,000
But because of that, whatever that prejudice that had been built into her life, and I don't know if it was from the immigrant experience, when I look back, for example, she went to flushing high school, when I look back at her picture, she's got black kids in her class in the 1920s.

96
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:55,000
I'm like, well, I don't get it. I don't understand the disconnect. Right? So anyway, so those were some of the early experiences that I had, both my mother criticizing who I associated with, and my mother criticizing anybody of color.

97
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:09,000
The Puerto Rican mailman was going to poison our dogs, the this, the that. I mean, incredible depth of real. And I think came from her own insecurity is clearly where it came from. Right?

98
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:18,000
So you talk about a number of these incidents. Do you remember what, when you first had some inclination of race?

99
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:30,000
Well, I think, at this day camp I worked out, I was in college. In high school, there was one African American student in my entire four years that I was in school.

100
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:40,000
And he was a senior when I was a freshman, and he was the student body president. And then the next four years, the next three years after that, there was never another black student.

101
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:55,000
There were Jewish students, and I remember not quite understanding what that was about, not quite getting it that there were differences in religious beliefs or practices type of thing.

102
00:12:55,000 --> 00:13:08,000
I remember in terms of religion, my mother was Catholic, my father was Lutheran, but we never went to church. So kids would say to me, well, what religion are you? And I'd say, oh, I'm Catholic. And they would say, well, we don't see you at church. And I'm like, well, I don't go to church.

103
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:20,000
Like it was some badge of honor, right, that I didn't go to church, and they would like criticize me. So when I was a junior in high school, and I got my driver's license, I started being the super religious type.

104
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:27,000
Go to Mass every morning. I got my first communion. I did all that stuff, right? And then...

105
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:44,000
And then... How long did that last? Well, it lasted probably into my... The zealousness didn't last after I got to college, but I was pretty regular going to Mass when I was in college until my senior year in college.

106
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:58,000
And I go to Cornell, where my brother is now a freshman, and that was Easter break. We go to Cornell, and so I go to confession, right? And I tell this priest that I knew...

107
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:08,000
I kind of... It's so funny. Everything was so disconnected on some level. So I kind of know that it's not good to read these philosophy...

108
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:19,000
I'm taking a philosophy course at Skimler, right? And I kind of knew it wasn't according to church doctrine. You weren't supposed to read this stuff because it would poison your mind, right?

109
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:31,000
So I tell the priest that I'm reading Locke, and Grasso, and Hagel, and Marx, and so on, and he's like a guest, and he's giving me all these Hail Mary's that I have to say, and this...

110
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:39,000
You know, the pens I have to do because I'm reading these scholarly books, I walked out of that confessional, and I said, I'm finished with Catholicism, right?

111
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:46,000
And in fact, I was finished except that, you know, I would go to weddings and funerals and so on.

112
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:52,000
You've mentioned to me before that your godmother was Spanish being...

113
00:14:52,000 --> 00:15:00,000
She was Mexican, and the way that she got to be my godmother is my father and her husband worked on a book together.

114
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:17,000
And he was a scientist, and they had moved here from Mexico. I never really understood the circumstances or how that happened. But anyway, they worked on a book together, and so I'm sure in the process of working on that book that my mother got to know Lucy...

115
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:25,000
Lucy was her name, Lucy Droz, got to know her, and asked her to be my godmother when I was born.

116
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:37,000
So then later on, I would say to my mother, well, if you're... And she would also criticize Lucy, my godmother, she would say she speaks broken English, she...

117
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:44,000
I don't know, all the other things that she would think of about a Spanish-speaking Mexican woman at that point in time.

118
00:15:44,000 --> 00:16:00,000
So that was like in the early 1940s, mid-40s type of thing. But I mean, I think I said it to her later, probably in the 50s, I said, well, how come you asked her to be my godmother if you have such contempt for her, you know, her persona?

119
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:28,000
And my mother said, well, she's the only Catholic I knew at the time. So that also speaks to me of my mother's isolation, that she didn't have a lot of friends, and she never really did have a lot of friends in her life, except later on when she started doing a lot of service, clubs, and things like that, you know, going to the nursing home and giving gifts out to people who were sick or going to the children's home, to the orphans home, whatever it was in that community at that time.

120
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:57,000
So it spoke to her, to me, it spoke to her isolation and her fear of having conversation about things with people. And I don't know, was that her upbringing, probably so, it probably was very closed and very, you know, you know, and also, another thing that's funny is she would talk to me about this woman who lived on her block and flushing, who was a communist, and so she had a total contempt for communism.

121
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:26,000
And I was like, well, what does that mean? What's that about? Right? I mean, all these things just didn't sink. Right. And then later on, of course, when I was, when I was both in the movement, and when I was a graduate student, I began to understand about the communist organizing around the globe and what that meant, what it signified, and of course, the Russian Revolution was very much in people's minds at that time when I was a grad student, and the African liberation, and I was a grad student.

122
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:45,000
And there were some movements and so on, so that was like steeped in all of that, studying all of that and understanding the contradictions. So, it all kind of fell into place, but I never really, my mother never really explained the depth of her, her anxiety about that stuff.

123
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:47,000
How do you spell DROs?

124
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:55,000
Okay. Can you tell us about your experience in college at Skidmore?

125
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:11,000
Sure. So, you know, I think I was kind of like a regular middle-class college kid. I don't think I stood out at all. I don't think I, I don't remember anything.

126
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:23,000
So, the thing that I began to remember is when in my sophomore year, I ran for student body secretary, and I ran against a woman who beat me.

127
00:18:23,000 --> 00:18:40,000
And then a woman came up to me, and she said, would you like to run for NSA secretary? So, that's NSA was the National Student Association, US National Student Association, which was the organization that represented college student leaders all around the country.

128
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:54,000
And I had no clue what that was, and I said, sure, why not? Right? So, I obviously was into some kind of service or giving back or, you know, being engaged in the civic life of the community.

129
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:03,000
So, I ran for NSA secretary, and, or maybe it was NSA vice chairman, I think it was because there was a chairman and a vice chairman.

130
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:16,000
And as a result, I was allowed to go or give an opportunity to go to Ohio Wesley on that summer to the National Student Congress. So, it was, that was the life changing experience.

131
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:24,000
Now, is that the meeting every summer that brought people together?

132
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:30,000
Exactly. But that wasn't the several weeks seminar that Connie Curry was, no, that actually.

133
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:37,000
No, that's different. Well, in May, this was 57, I think, was it 57?

134
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:41,000
She started in that job in 60, so.

135
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:49,000
So, 58, this was the 1958 student congress, and it did bring people together from all across the country.

136
00:19:49,000 --> 00:20:01,000
And there were people talking about South African part-time, there were people talking about segregation in the South, but not as intensely as a few years later.

137
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:03,000
And that was a life changing?

138
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:09,000
That was life changing because here were all these students that were engaged in talking about the world.

139
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:20,000
And I'm talking about political formations and organizing and movements and oppression and all of those words that I wasn't really familiar with, right?

140
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:26,000
So, I go back to campus, I was a psych major before that, so I changed my major to political science.

141
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:29,000
Well, first I was a math major, okay, that's another story.

142
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:35,000
I was a math major because my father anticipated the rise of computers and the importance of computers.

143
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:40,000
And he said to me, you've got to be a math major. Look, you're very good in math, which I was.

144
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:53,000
And you've got to be a math major. So, I go to Skidmore, there's one professor in the math department, a woman, who I just didn't feel, you know, sink.

145
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:59,000
I didn't have any synchronicity with her. So, I changed my major to psychology when I was a freshman.

146
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:06,000
But then I come back after my experience at the National Student Congress, I come back, change my major to political science.

147
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:17,000
And that's when I begin to really delve into political ideas and debates and ideological discussions and all of that kind of thing.

148
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:32,000
So, that's kind of why that was like changing. And then the next spring, I run for student body president, the spring of my junior year, which is 59 spring, I lose to the same woman that beat me for secretary.

149
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:43,000
And then I'm asked to run for NSA chairman, I do that. And so then I go to the National Student Congress that summer, it's at the University of Illinois, Champaign or Banna.

150
00:21:43,000 --> 00:21:59,000
Again, students come from all over and you know, you have this incredible experience you learn. And some of us, the initial thing that we got involved in was student voice on campus.

151
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:16,000
So, it was about having a say in how good or bad the professors were or having a say in the kind of college life. You know, mundane things like what the dormitory hours were or whether we had an honor system in the dorms.

152
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:20,000
And you know, there were a lot of different things that we wanted to take on.

153
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:25,000
Did women have different rules on campus than men?

154
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:41,000
Well, it was a girl, it was a women's college. It was all women until more recently. Yeah, it was all women. But we had pretty strict rules. And we had this thing called in local parentis, which meant the college was standing in the place of your parents.

155
00:22:41,000 --> 00:23:00,000
And so, it was very regimented. And if you know, there were women who went out on a date and you know, came in the back window, somebody helped them unlock the window and come in so they could sneak past the house mother type of thing. But it was very, you know, it was very cocoon-like type of thing.

156
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:09,000
So, you started going into these NSA meetings. Are you, is there any sense on campus of rebelling against this sort of strict control?

157
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:21,000
Some of it's there. I don't think that's the major thing. I mean, I think one of the things that the first campaign that I kind of got involved in was around the National Defense Education Act.

158
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:38,000
And I think it's because this was an NSA campaign. So, this was to fight against the loyalty oath in the National Defense Education Act, which said if you were going to get a scholarship or a loan from the federal government, you had to swear that you were not then or had ever been a communist, a member of the Communist Party.

159
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:52,000
I forgot how the oath went. But I had taken the civil liberties course from this fabulous professor about loyalty oaths. I mean, one of the pieces was about loyalty oaths. You shouldn't be forced to take a loyalty oath.

160
00:23:52,000 --> 00:24:06,000
So, I'm applying my political science and getting involved in this campaign. So, we had students writing letters to their local papers in their hometowns. And we had people sending postcards to their congressmen and that kind of thing.

161
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:16,000
So, that's again, it's a disconnection to what's the role of a citizen and democracy and how can we encourage that citizenship and that involvement.

162
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:25,000
And that was, again, that was the big NSA mantra was involvement in your life of your community or your college or whatever.

163
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:36,000
Do you remember here about the civil rights movement or what you're talking about in much?

164
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:49,000
Well, yes. And in fact, what happened is that when we're doing this National Defense Education Act campaign, this is early 1960.

165
00:24:49,000 --> 00:25:05,000
And I had, you know, okay, yeah. So, I'm the NSA chairman. I'm getting all this information through NSA either through phone calls or through letters. And 1960 happens and the student sit-ins happen.

166
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:26,000
So, we, or, and I don't remember if NSA encouraged us to do something, but we had these big meetings on campus. We had a Woolworths in our town in Saratoga Springs. So, we began to have these student meetings where we debated what we could do to support the Southern students.

167
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:44,000
Or if we should, I think part of the question was, should we support the Southern students? And I actually have a leaflet, which I should have gotten out to show you. I can get it later. It says, it's something like the right to eat. It's a human right and black student.

168
00:25:44,000 --> 00:26:09,000
It says Negro students in the South don't have the right to eat at lunch counters. And this is outrageous and shocking. And we need to come together to discuss this and talk about what to do. And so we did, we did that. We came together. And we decided after four very heated meetings. I mean, it was my first experience with what democratic discussion and debate might be like, because we had every point of view in the, in the book.

169
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:21,000
So we decided we would plan a protest and we took 200 women students from campus down to the Woolworths, walked around the Woolworths and came back to campus.

170
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:38,000
So there were a couple of freshmen students that said, we can't stop here. Actually, a freshman and a sophomore student and they said, we can't stop here. We can't do this. We got to keep going. So we sent four students. The plan was we sent four students every hour the next day to pick it at the Woolworths.

171
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:55,000
The first four students that went got picked up by the police, take into the police station. And one of the students father was an attorney. So she knew that you couldn't, you couldn't, you didn't have to give your name or your address until you were actually charged with a crime.

172
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:12,000
So the paper, the front page of the Saratoga paper that day has four students like this with their hands over their eyes blocking their faces. And the article is skitties more than they bargained for.

173
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:32,000
And the editorial says we were on lady like we never should have picketed. What was that about the police are prepared to charge the students with a union with a statute that was meant for union busting basically no picketing within a hundred yards of something or other.

174
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:47,000
But the Woolworths is private property. This is the beginning of the shopping center boom where the, this whole square and the parking lot are owned by the corporation. And so you can't go next to the store to disrupt the business at all.

175
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:48,000
So.

176
00:27:48,000 --> 00:28:17,000
Yes, yes, nobody continues. No, the panic button is hit. The president of the college calls us in. We sit down in his office. He reads us the right act. He tells us we have the season to this that this is not appropriate. It's not right. And so we can and actually spring break was the next day. So we kind of the spring break dissipated the energy.

177
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:41,000
And as I go ahead. I was shocked. I mean, again, you know, you grow up with the Bill of Rights and the first amendment freedoms and you think everybody has the right to express their opinion. And we had we had peacefully done the March down is maybe five or six blocks from campus. So we went down and then around the Woolworths and came back.

178
00:28:41,000 --> 00:29:03,000
And actually in the Skidmore history book, there are some pictures of that fabulous picket. And so yes, I think we were shocked. We were like, what got arrested? I mean, or taken to the police station not charged formally released to in local parentless release to the father of the president of the college. Right. So.

179
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:32,000
So yeah, so that was pretty and so we really understood that we were fighting for our own right to be free and that there was a connection between supporting the Southern students and our own exercise of our own rights. So that again for me, that was a lesson in how everything is connected that if that if you step out a line, so to speak and you protest something that's not acceptable to the people in power, you also get, you know, in this case, you know,

180
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:51,000
they slept, slept down, you know, because no untoward consequence, nobody got a record and nobody got, you know, fingerprinted and nobody got handcuffed and type of thing. But still you get you get cut off from being able to do that kind of thing. So.

181
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:58,000
You said that the spring break kind of dissipated the energy. Did you always do many kind of protest activity afterwards?

182
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:18,000
We didn't and I really, well, just another thing now that spring break was when Snick was founded and I considered going to Shaw to be at that founding meeting. But I was terrified of my mother's response. And in fact, that's, I had had a letter in the new in the Hastings newspaper.

183
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:39,000
They lived in Hastings on Hudson. I had a letter in the Hastings newspaper just before I came home for spring break about the National Defense Education Act, which that like through them for a loop, she told me don't show up in the house until after dark because she didn't want her and she was having some kind of women over for two years, something like that.

184
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:58,000
So, but she didn't want me to be have any relationship with any of her friends or her, you know, whatever her service buddies. So, so that. So then at the same time, I'm really terrified that if I try to go to Shaw, she'll be really upset and angry.

185
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:18,000
So, I didn't push it, but the fresh one of the freshmen students who had pushed for us to go down and pick it the second day, she went to actually her name was Linda Chase and I've actually lost total track of her. I can't find her anywhere. So, I don't know if she dropped out of Skidmore or left Skidmore after two years, I think.

186
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:28,000
But she, I'm always curious is like what was her journey after that? Where did she go and what did she do? Yeah, nice.

187
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:35,000
Yeah, yeah, because she's here, she is a freshman and she's pushing that we continue and we escalate and so on.

188
00:31:35,000 --> 00:31:45,000
Can you remember, can you go back and are you able to recreate what you were thinking about the SNCC conference or how you knew about it or what it meant to you?

189
00:31:46,000 --> 00:32:09,000
Well, I think because I think I thought the students were extremely courageous, the sitting students. And because I felt so kind of like the cover being pulled off the US for me, all the kind of the ideals and values that we believed in and then the contradiction showing up that black students couldn't sit at lunch.

190
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:29,000
I mean, I was I was floored. I think because again, we didn't grow up with this. I mean, I grew up with a prejudice mother, but I didn't grow up where black people couldn't go into grocery stores or or or Woolworth lunch counters or whatever if they were in if they lived in those communities.

191
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:41,000
I mean, I never there were lots of things as a white person I never thought about. So I didn't think about the absence of black people in my school or the absence of black people in my community. I didn't think about that.

192
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:58,000
So I didn't understand the privilege that white people had in that era, like especially the the GI Bill of Rights or the the FHA and the VA loans for houses that were where you were required to buy a house.

193
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:19,000
And the stable community and stable community for sure meant a racially homogeneous community. So, but we didn't you know that the those privileges didn't really we didn't have a good understanding of what you know and nobody nobody alerted us to the fact that there were these discrepancies.

194
00:33:19,000 --> 00:33:29,000
So, students not able to either a lunch counter that was the tip of iceberg. You know, Miss Baker, oh, Miss Baker, oh, Miss Ella Baker was very much a mentor for all of us.

195
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:38,000
She always talked about it's more than a hamburger. So, we had to move from lunch counter sit in to some bigger, bigger issues.

196
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:42,000
Do you remember how you found out about the Smith County Conference or the Smith County?

197
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:52,000
I'm not sure it must have it must have been it must have been through NSA and and maybe it was the sitting students because it wasn't called snick at the time right.

198
00:33:52,000 --> 00:34:02,000
Yeah, it would have been the sitting students are gathering a Shaw in Raleigh and they're going to talk about you know the next steps or their strategy or something like that.

199
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:17,000
So, I'm sure it was through NSA that I heard about it and maybe NSA invited some of the students who had been leaders on the campus leading the because all over one of the things we did was of course this is in the nature of competition.

200
00:34:17,000 --> 00:34:32,000
And on this leaflet that I that I've saved, we talk about how at Yale and Wesley, wellesley and Smith and also and they're supporting the sitting students. So, we need to be supporting the sitting students as well right.

201
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:37,000
So, exactly, exactly, exactly.

202
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:42,000
And when you graduated, do you want to work for the NSA?

203
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:52,000
When I graduated I was invited to be part of something called the International Student Relations Seminar. The ISRIS is that right?

204
00:34:52,000 --> 00:35:02,000
Yes, the ISRIS, the International Relations students, the International Student Relations Seminar. So, that you live in Philadelphia for two months.

205
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:14,000
There were about 12 of us in this ISRIS session. There were two women and all the rest were men, very intellectual men.

206
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:28,000
And what it was, it turned out only again in retrospect it was the training ground for future NSA officers and for CIA service.

207
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:41,000
So, the National Student Association's International Program was funded by the CIA through a lot of subterfusions, through foundation, conduits and that kind of thing.

208
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:49,000
And then when the student travelers went overseas to either Latin America or Europe or the Soviet Union or Africa, they took notes on who were the emerging leaders, who were the students that were organizing the

209
00:35:49,000 --> 00:36:04,000
liberation movements, what were their ideologies, were they sympathetic to the US or not, and then all of those notes went directly to the CIA.

210
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:14,000
So, it was the way the CIA, the notes and I'm sure the interviews, I mean, there's a new book, which is actually on my shelf over there.

211
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:25,000
That red and blue book, you see right there, what's it called, Patriotic Brewer, Patriotic Betrayal?

212
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:40,000
Yeah, sure, let's hold it up. So, this is by a woman who, I believe her husband also, they had been in the CIA, they had been in the NSA.

213
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:57,000
And when they learned about the CIA connection, they were like shocked also, and so she said about doing this scholarship, this scholarship, doing this scholarship, and it just came out maybe 2011, 2012, 2013, and something like that.

214
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:03,000
I know it was a real shock to a lot of people when they learned of the connection between that and the CIA.

215
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:13,000
What the students, this is a little bit of field, but what the students who are traveling overseas and taking these notes, do they know what they're doing?

216
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:23,000
Some of them do, some of them do. The way it worked was this. First of all, in my estrus, there was a guy who was already a CIA on the CIA payroll.

217
00:37:23,000 --> 00:37:35,000
He's pretending, I don't know his whole story, but I guess he's pretending that he's in the seminar because he was a student leader on campus or something like that.

218
00:37:35,000 --> 00:37:51,000
So, there are plants, there are CIA plants in these seminars. There are also former NSA officers who have been recruited by the CIA, who are the trainers for these sessions.

219
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:59,000
And of course, we're going through a country by country synopsis. What are the student movements in those countries? What do they look like?

220
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:09,000
What are the politics of the way governments are constructed? And that kind of thing. So that's another piece. So there's CIA agents in the estrus.

221
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:17,000
There's CIA agents who are former NSA officers, and nobody tells you that they're CIA. That's all hidden.

222
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:33,000
And then the third thing is, it's the way that they vet people for NSA office. So if you're in this estrus, you have this potential to become the international vice president, for example, of the National Student Association.

223
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:41,000
And then what happens is once the student congress happens, and there's all this manipulation to get the right people in office.

224
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:54,000
So they're clearly looking for people who are going to be sympathetic to the US foreign policy constellation of issues, and therefore sympathetic to the CIA's values.

225
00:38:54,000 --> 00:39:02,000
So then once you're in office, they take you out and they tell you that the CIA is bankrolling the international program.

226
00:39:02,000 --> 00:39:20,000
And they make you witty, witty, witty, w-i-t-t-i-n-g. So then the code word becomes, are you witty? And everybody, you know, if you're not witty, you say, and if you are witty, you say, yes, I'm witty.

227
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:31,000
And so then they can have their conversations. So whether, and I haven't read enough of this patriotic portrayal to know, if the student travelers knew that they were feeding,

228
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:47,000
did they know that the CIA had a hand in bankrolling their work? Because that's what happened, the travel fees and all of that were donated by the CIA through these foundation conduits.

229
00:39:47,000 --> 00:40:06,000
Well, I know that Tim Jenkins was active in NSA as a Howard student and his body president, and he has told me that he had hoped to be the vice chair of the vice president for international affairs and got sort of maneuvered over the domestic community.

230
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:19,000
Yes, they probably didn't trust him. They probably didn't trust him. And he's a black student too, and that's unusual in the NSA. It's somewhat unusual to have a black officer. So he gets maneuvered over to national vice president.

231
00:40:19,000 --> 00:40:23,000
Of course, it's interesting because then he's in the position of national vice president.

232
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:25,000
Exactly. And the sit-in star.

233
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:28,000
Exactly. And becomes an advocate within the head.

234
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:30,000
Exactly. Exactly. Exactly.

235
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:42,000
So the woman, there was a woman who was the international affairs vice president of the IAVP, and apparently the year before this, apparently they didn't trust her either.

236
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:52,000
And so they didn't make her waiting. And the guy who was the administrator of the international program had to carry all that secrecy and the decisions and the strategy.

237
00:40:52,000 --> 00:40:58,000
So, you know, there was clearly a lot of sexism as well as racism in the day.

238
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:10,000
So after you went to that workshop, the ISRIS, so I go to the National Student Congress, which is in Minnesota that year. And one fabulous thing about that.

239
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:12,000
Is this the year you graduated?

240
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:19,000
Yes, that's 60. It's 1960. So I go to Minnesota that summer. And I can't remember.

241
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:25,000
Is that when Tim is elected? Or he's elected the year before? I can't remember anyway.

242
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:31,000
Tim's forged for the NSA, maybe 59, 600.

243
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:35,000
Okay. So he's in office when I go to the ISRIS that summer. Okay.

244
00:41:35,000 --> 00:41:43,000
So, so, so what was I starting to say?

245
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:59,000
Oh, you were talking about going to the Congress in Minnesota. Yes. So one of the things that CIA also did, which you only learned about in retrospect, is they brought Algerian revolutionary students to the US for a month.

246
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:09,000
And under the auspices of NSA, right, to have a conference and meeting. So I go to Minnesota a little bit early because I'm in this ISRIS program.

247
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:24,000
And I experience the energy and the enthusiasm and the excitement of these students who are meeting and singing and and they're in solidarity with each other in such phenomenal ways.

248
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:32,000
I can't, I'm just, I'm just swept up by the by the energy that they're putting out in their meetings, right?

249
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:43,000
I mean, I wasn't in most of their meetings, but I was in some of their social gatherings and the singing and the, and of course I didn't understand the words because it was in French, but it was still.

250
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:47,000
So when you're talking about the group and the energy and their support, it's the Algerian students.

251
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:54,000
It's the Algerian students. Exactly. Exactly. And these are the students who then become the leaders of the Algerian revolution.

252
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:12,000
So go back or maybe they're already involved. I can't, I don't know the dates of the Algerian revolution, but, but to me that was just, that was a cathartic experience to see this excitement about fighting for freedom, basically, is what it was, right?

253
00:43:13,000 --> 00:43:25,000
So after the student congress, I go to California. I'm, I have a boyfriend who is also in the israce, who's going to be a political science grad student at Berkeley.

254
00:43:25,000 --> 00:43:37,000
So I take a job as a campus traveler to sell tours to Europe for NSA. And I go to Berkeley, I live there, I've actually lived in Oakland.

255
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:48,000
And I travel to every college on the west coast, Oregon, California, Idaho, Washington, et cetera, every single campus that exists at the time.

256
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:54,000
And that was kind of, you know, I did it by myself. I was on a bus going from college to college.

257
00:43:55,000 --> 00:44:07,000
And then I get a call in November, late November, saying that the assistant to the president of NSA is going to resign and would I come to live in Philadelphia to be the assistant to the president.

258
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:17,000
So I do, I had broken up with this guy by then, right? So I don't have any other ties to Berkeley, except I loved it out there. And so I come back to Philadelphia.

259
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:23,000
And I, I'm the one who organizes the National Student Congress for the next summer at the University of Wisconsin.

260
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:25,000
So that would have been fall of 60, yeah.

261
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:39,000
This is, yes, this is November of 60. I go back to Philadelphia. And I live in Philadelphia from November of 60 up until summer of 61, when the National Student Congress takes place at the University of Wisconsin.

262
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:48,000
And I'm the person, the logistics person, the one who figures out all the dormitory stuff, the rooms, the audio visual setup, the lunches.

263
00:44:48,000 --> 00:44:56,000
I go out to Wisconsin through four times and negotiate with the university officials. And that's kind of like a big step for me.

264
00:44:56,000 --> 00:45:08,000
I'm a year out of college and I'm given this huge responsibility to pull this conference off. And I do. And then this is the summer that I meet the SDS people.

265
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:28,000
And I meet the liberal study group with quotes around it happens at the Congress, that Al Haber and Tom Hayden and others are pulling people together to have discussions about US imperialism and capitalism and the war, the Cold War and all of that context.

266
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:49,000
So this is 61. In fact, Port Huron is 62 summer. So it's the up, it's the run up to Port Huron. So SDS is obviously using some of these forums as ways to identify students who have similar thinking and can be recruited for the building of the SDS chapters around the country.

267
00:45:49,000 --> 00:46:04,000
Sure. Were all of the NSA sort of leaders elected? Well, I guess you just said that there was a woman who was the domestic vice chair the year before 10.

268
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:10,000
She wasn't the domestic. She was the international vice chair. And they didn't trust her. Yeah.

269
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:31,000
So were most of the NSA national officers men? Yes. Yes. It was very rare to have a woman as there were three. There was the president and then the NABP, the National Affairs Vice President and the IABP, the International Affairs Vice President. So there were three officers basically. And they were mostly men.

270
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:51,000
And what about the position that you had as sort of a system? Is that generally a female job? I think it would have been either. It was just somebody who had the logistical administrative experience and could do that. Yeah, it could do that kind of work. So I think mostly it was women, but you know, I don't know.

271
00:46:51,000 --> 00:47:15,000
I think it was a semi-secretary thing. Yeah. I mean, I think. Yeah. I think so. You mentioned that you were at the 1960 Congress in Minnesota. Do you remember there was a panel that there was in Casey gave a fabulous speech? I remember she gave. And I think maybe I don't know if Tim was on the panel too, but there was a.

272
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:39,000
I remember something and that was the summer that Connie also had the Southern student human relations seminar. Right? And so brought Southern students, black and white Southern students. I can remember Casey's speech. I mean, I can remember being in the audience and how electric it felt. And you know, she was taking a step way out there and that was pretty powerful.

273
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:59,000
Yeah. So I think that there was Tim, I'm sure, was part of it, but there was a group that was leading a push for the NSA to pass a resolution in support of the city and then some Southern students are opposing it. And I think Casey gets recruited to be on his panel. So the students. Okay.

274
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:06,000
She gets recruited to be on the panel to oppose the push or they think she's going to.

275
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:13,000
Well, I think that the NSA leadership who was trying to get the resolution passed. I see.

276
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:21,000
I was looking for supporters to put on the Southern panel. Okay. Okay. I understand. Okay. Okay. That's some backstory. I think John.

277
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:29,000
Robinson on December 8th, 2015 in her home in Baltimore. And we're here with the Civil Rights History Project,

278
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:36,000
co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

279
00:48:36,000 --> 00:48:43,000
And also here is John Bishop and Gouha Shankar. And thank you very much.

280
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:49,000
Oh, that's my pleasure. And can you tell us when and where you were born and about your family?

281
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:57,000
Sure. I was born on January 8th, 1939. And I was born in New York City.

282
00:48:57,000 --> 00:49:05,000
My father was a professor at maybe I don't know, full professor. And you know, now that I know that I know assistant associate,

283
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:12,000
whatever, I don't know what kind of professor he was, but he was a professor of physics and chemistry at New York University.

284
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:21,000
And he had grown up on a farm. So he got a college opportunity at Franklin and Marshall College in Pennsylvania.

285
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:31,000
And then he went to NYU and got a PhD. And that was like big for his family having, you know, actually his parents were Pennsylvania German.

286
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:41,000
They barely spoke English. So for him, that was big to be catapulted into this position.

287
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:51,000
And then my mother was born in New York City in a working class family born in, I don't know if she was born in flushing, but New York City anyway.

288
00:49:51,000 --> 00:50:01,000
Her mother was the daughter of an Irish immigrant and her father was the son of German immigrants.

289
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:11,000
And so she grew up, she was the first of her family to go to college. She went to NYU also, which is where she met my dad.

290
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:20,000
And then I was born in 39. My brother was born in 42. And what else do you want to know about that?

291
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:23,000
What was your family like? What was your growing experience?

292
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:32,000
Oh, okay, okay. So my growing up experience, both my mother and father, this was like during World War II, right?

293
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:45,000
So my father moved, we moved to Cambridge, Massachusetts, and my father worked at MIT in the radiation lab, which was the laboratory where the atomic bomb was being constructed.

294
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:55,000
And I don't think he knew what part in developing the bomb he was playing, but he had something to do with radar.

295
00:50:55,000 --> 00:51:05,000
And so we had moved to Cambridge, my brother was, well, we were both pre-school kindergarten age when we lived there.

296
00:51:05,000 --> 00:51:16,000
And I can remember the air raids. I can remember the blocking our, this is again World War II, I can remember the threat of war.

297
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:26,000
So blocking the light from our house with dark curtains or turning the lights off or when an air raid would happen hiding under the bed.

298
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:42,000
I can remember all those things, and I think that connected with my later anti-war sentiments, because as a kid when you live that trauma, you're not conscious of what those feelings are, but later on it comes to the surface.

299
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:55,000
So there was that piece. Then we moved to back to New York, and we moved eventually, by the time I was in Second Grade, we moved to a suburb pleasant bill in New York,

300
00:51:55,000 --> 00:52:07,000
where there was a new laboratory that my father was working at. He was kind of the chief scientist of a, it was called a general precision equipment, or general precision, GPL.

301
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:14,000
It was called general precision labs first and became general precision equipment, and then it became something else after that.

302
00:52:14,000 --> 00:52:39,000
But so it was in the era where these labs were consolidating and bigger companies were buying them. But I can remember him coming home, tormented and upset and really angry and sometimes crying because of the competition and the cutthroat nature of the job that he had and the people around him.

303
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:52,000
So it was a very collaborative type of person, and as a scientist I think he wanted that collaboration, but there was a lot of jealousy and there was a lot of back biting, and he was just tortured by all of that happening.

304
00:52:52,000 --> 00:53:09,000
So I think then let Anne will jump forward ahead. Some of my feelings, like when my brother and I were in college, we talked about how we were not going to work in corporate America because of what we had seen my dad go through.

305
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:19,000
We were like absolutely no corporate America for us, and that was my brother too. He became a veterinarian, but never worked for a big corporate firm.

306
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:33,000
So that was kind of a key thing in my values formation, I think. And again reflecting back, I don't know where the values that I got, the progressive values that I got actually came from.

307
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:45,000
And there's other pieces like my mother was very prejudiced and very, very anti black, anti anybody of color. And I would push back against that.

308
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:59,000
I think on one level because she also was critical of every friend I ever had. So and those were white friends. So she would say I don't like her, her parents are immigrants, and I would say but wait a minute, your grandmother was an immigrant.

309
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:14,000
Or she would say I don't like this family because they're working class or when the first boyfriend I had was a son of a truck driver. And I would be like wait there's a contradiction here. Like you grew up the daughter of a carpenter.

310
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:27,000
It just didn't compute to me. So the fact that she was prejudiced and then some other incidents that happened which I can tell you, but I'll let you ask another question.

311
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:43,000
When you talk about your dad and the work being very competitive and how upsetting, how does that work if he's in the lab? Is it competitive with other scientists or is there pressure on him because of competition between companies?

312
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:44,000
Do you have a sense of that?

313
00:54:44,000 --> 00:54:56,000
No, I think because it was it was called GPL, General Precision Labs, but it wasn't a laboratory per se. I mean they were involved in in the first television production. They were involved in a lot of different equipment.

314
00:54:56,000 --> 00:55:11,000
The competition was mostly from if I can remember this well enough, from non-scientists who wanted to be in his position in the corporate structure. In other words the corporate ladder.

315
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:31,000
So he was given a particular role because of his knowledge and his library. He had books all over his library, all these scientific magazines and every night he would be reading and pouring over all this kind of cutting edge science because this is the late 40s where science is just blossoming.

316
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:50,000
But his work is more of a managerial because of the knowledge that he has. He is overseeing some of the scientific work but it's not pure scientific.

317
00:55:50,000 --> 00:56:15,000
And so he's feeling this competitiveness and this absolute backstabbing and that kind of thing. So it was kind of like this turmoil and this tension that he brought home almost every night and then it bled over to my mother and her anxieties about her life having grown up working class and being both of them are feeling not accepted in their new class.

318
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:27,000
In other words they're both feeling very uncomfortable when they go to a party or when they host somebody at the house they're like very almost like having six thumbs.

319
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:41,000
And they don't talk about that but you can tell that that's their discomfort. They never joined a country club. I think that would have been like they didn't have the quote social graces that they thought was expected of them.

320
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:51,000
I'm sure some of the other people were also going through the same thing but because nobody talked about anything then nobody shared any of their deepest feelings.

321
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:59,000
Did you have a sense of this when you were young or is this sort of looking back and trying to make sense of what you did experience?

322
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:09,000
It's partly looking back but it's partly I can remember the tension around. I can remember my father's anguish and anxiety and anger.

323
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:21,000
I can remember that very very vividly but I didn't know how to piece it together. I didn't understand the class stuff until I got, until I was out of the snake probably or in the snake.

324
00:57:21,000 --> 00:57:37,000
I don't know. I didn't really understand that and I clearly didn't understand the racial prejudice. Like when I was in high school my brother and I worked at a YMCA camp and there was a black woman who was a vassar student who was a counselor.

325
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:45,000
Now you have to understand my mother wanted me to go to one of the hot shot women's colleges and I was like totally resistant to that.

326
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:57,000
No I'm not going to Smith vassar Wellesley Radcliffe. No I'm not going there. So I picked Skidmore which was kind of up in those ranks but it was like a lesser than school.

327
00:57:57,000 --> 00:58:07,000
Of course my shock when I got to Skidmore was my roommate brought in 30 pairs of shoes and this is in 1956 and I'm like what is this?

328
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:17,000
I thought I was rejecting this upper class life at these other colleges and bumped right smack into it.

329
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:25,000
But anyway vassar was one of the schools that my mother had wanted me to go to and even look at I refused to even go visit these schools.

330
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:33,000
So here we have an African American woman vassar student on the staff of the YMCA day camp.

331
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:39,000
My brother and I because we're the brother sister team we decide to host a party at our house.

332
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:49,000
So we host a party at our house all the counselors come we have a great time then everybody leaves and then I'm looking for my mother and it's like where where is she?

333
00:58:49,000 --> 00:58:58,000
My dad says well she's down the basement. She had a little room a little room like an office room where she did sewing and crafts and stuff.

334
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:07,000
So I go down there and she's in tears and I'm like well what the heck is going on? And she's like you will never live us down you brought a nigger into the house.

335
00:59:07,000 --> 00:59:14,000
Well the neighbors think and I'm like well first my first comment was worth dark nobody nobody saw.

336
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:26,000
I mean that was like the the utilitarian way but the second thing is wait a minute this is a woman who we work with every day she's a vassar student like what objection could you have to that?

337
00:59:26,000 --> 00:59:35,000
But because of that whatever that prejudice that had been built into her life and I don't know if it was from the immigrant experience.

338
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:45,000
When I look back for example she went to flushing high school when I look back at her picture she's got black kids in her class in the 1920s right.

339
00:59:45,000 --> 01:00:04,000
I'm like well I don't get it I don't I don't understand the disconnect right so anyway so so those were some of the early experiences that I had both my mother criticizing who I associated with and my mother criticizing anybody of color.

340
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:19,000
The Puerto Rican mailman was going to poison our dogs the this the that I mean incredible depth of of real and I think came from her own insecurity is is clearly what it where it came from right.

341
01:00:19,000 --> 01:00:28,000
So you talk about a number of these incidents do you remember what when you first had some inclination of race?

342
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:40,000
Well I think I at this day camp I worked out I was in college in high school there was one African American student in my entire four years that I was in school.

343
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:49,000
And he was a senior when I was a freshman and he was the student body president and then the next four years the next three years after that there was never another black student.

344
01:00:49,000 --> 01:01:04,000
There were Jewish students and I remember not quite understanding what that was about not quite getting it that there were differences in religious beliefs or practices type of thing.

345
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:18,000
I remember in terms of religion my mother was Catholic my father was Lutheran but we never went to church so kids would say to me what religion are you and I'd say I'm Catholic and they would say well we don't see you at church and I'm like well I don't go to church like it was some badge of I'm not going to go to church.

346
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:36,000
So when I was a junior in high school and I got my driver's license I started being the super religious type go to mass every morning I got my first communion I did all that stuff.

347
01:01:36,000 --> 01:02:02,000
And then how long did that last? Well it lasted probably into my the zealousness didn't last after I got to college but I was pretty regular going to mass when I was in college until my senior year in college and I go to Cornell where my brother is now a freshman and that's a it was Easter break.

348
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:21,000
We go to Cornell and so I go to confession and I tell this priest that I knew I kind of that's so funny I was everything was so disconnected on some level so I kind of know that it's not good to read these philosophy I'm taking a philosophy course it's getting more right.

349
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:28,000
And I kind of knew it wasn't it wasn't according to church doctor and you weren't supposed to read this stuff because it would poison your mind right.

350
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:37,000
So I tell the priest that I'm reading luck and Grasso and Hagel and Marx and so on and he's like a guest and he's giving me.

351
01:02:37,000 --> 01:02:51,000
So can you tell us what the can you have memories of that Thanksgiving meeting that snick held at Howard in 1963.

352
01:02:51,000 --> 01:03:06,000
The the biggest memory I have of is the singing that's the most incredible thing standing in a circle singing singing all the freedom songs and then people with tears streaming down their eyes singing we shall

353
01:03:06,000 --> 01:03:27,000
overcome at the very end of the meeting I mean that's the I think that's the emotional connection that I had to the movement was the singing and the understanding how song really pushed you forward gave you some courage to do some things that you maybe had

354
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:56,000
hadn't dreamed that you would do and and the community that again the collectivity of that moment of those moments where people were singing and they were united in that in that power I mean it's kind of the same thing I described with the Algerian students and the the power of that that singing and that camaraderie that that those were the things because and you know partly it was probably because of the way I was raised without a lot of that feeling and emotion happening

355
01:03:56,000 --> 01:04:10,000
I don't know you know just so those moments those emotional moments where you could where you could open up and be connected with people where it's kind of your yeah the thing.

356
01:04:10,000 --> 01:04:16,000
You know I know some of these networks and some of these people are very interconnected with NSA and STS.

357
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:20,000
So I left with something out the Southern student freedom fund I'll come back to that.

358
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:32,000
And but I was so you you end up sort of focusing you're moving into the snake.

359
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:40,000
Do you have a sense of why you became more engaged with snake and as opposed to continuing with STS?

360
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:55,000
Absolutely absolutely good question because I was thinking I also didn't bring bring up the STS stuff completely so by so I go to California thinking that I'm going to with this other woman Becky Mills that we're going to start an STS chapter.

361
01:04:55,000 --> 01:05:02,000
And we just somehow never get it off the ground maybe because I get involved in the civil rights support work.

362
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:21,000
And but at the same time I'm staying connected with the STS because by the I can't remember if it's by the it's not the summer of 62 maybe it is the summer of 62 after Port Huron.

363
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:50,000
So summer of 62 I also go to the world youth festival in Helsinki which is another piece okay so the world youth festival is run by the Soviet block and it's under it's the it's wufti the wufti world forum of democratic youth which is the Soviet blocks name for this there's the wufti and there's another one that the the west uses the

364
01:05:50,000 --> 01:06:18,000
European's in the US but I can't remember its name off it so so I go to Helsinki go to Helsinki youth festival under the auspices of the IRS which is the international relations something seminar maybe I don't know it's a thing that Gloria Steinem is connected to it's funded by the CIA she knows it's funded by the CIA and this other guy Harold Bakken who was an NSA president back in the

365
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:46,000
late 40s early 50s so they recruit a whole bunch of us to go to Helsinki to be the alternative to the Soviet line but we're like no testing Easter west people we're like anti nuclear we're supposed to be the radical students from the US who are maybe socialist but not pro communist if you want to I mean that's like a weird distinction but they you know there was the democratic world

366
01:06:46,000 --> 01:07:10,000
but they you know there was the democratic socialist movement in the US so there was the Michael Harrington folks who were anti communist viciously anti communist those were the people that rambling now but those were the people that were the the fathers of of SDS meaning slid this the slid and lid the league for industrial democracy these were viciously anti communist

367
01:07:10,000 --> 01:07:39,000
socialist the Michael Harrington was one of that group and the norm in time the socialist so to speak so so and then slid was the student league for industrial democracy which was the student arm which was kind of the auspices under which SDS initially collected and then there was a break so I went to this meeting in New York I was I was put on the SDS executive committee and I don't remember when or why or

368
01:07:39,000 --> 01:08:09,000
or or how come but maybe because I was a student at Berkeley and they imagined that you know I would really be doing some organizing work at Berkeley I hadn't really cut my teeth on organizing yet but they put me there so so in the summer of 62 I believe after Port Huron the reason I didn't go to Port Huron is because I went to the I went to the world festival I went to the the Congress the world use Congress whatever it was called what did I say I was going to go and I was going to do something for the Congress I didn't want to do it and I was going to go to the Congress I went to the the Congress I went to the Congress the world use Congress whatever it was called what did I say

369
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:12,840
It was called the Festival of Democratic Youth, something like that.

370
01:08:12,840 --> 01:08:15,640
So I went to that instead of Port Huron.

371
01:08:15,640 --> 01:08:21,880
But when I came back, we were at a meeting in New York with the Lid, the League for Industrial

372
01:08:21,880 --> 01:08:23,040
Democracy people.

373
01:08:23,040 --> 01:08:27,800
And this was when the split happened between Lid and SDS.

374
01:08:27,800 --> 01:08:33,560
And other people can give you much better detail if this is an area of interest.

375
01:08:33,560 --> 01:08:39,720
And I can remember a guy named Mickey Most banging his head on the table and screaming,

376
01:08:39,720 --> 01:08:43,720
those bloody communists, they're this, they're that, they're this, and they're that.

377
01:08:43,720 --> 01:08:48,560
And of course, this is in the context of, right, this is post, the Stalin purges and all

378
01:08:48,560 --> 01:08:49,560
of that.

379
01:08:49,560 --> 01:08:50,560
What did I know about any of that stuff?

380
01:08:50,560 --> 01:08:51,560
I didn't know.

381
01:08:51,560 --> 01:08:55,400
You know, I'm probably not too many people in the US knew about that because it was kept

382
01:08:55,400 --> 01:08:56,400
under wraps.

383
01:08:56,400 --> 01:09:00,560
So, but this guy is just foaming at the mouth and he's really angry and pissed.

384
01:09:00,560 --> 01:09:09,760
And so I can remember those kind of emotional moments as the hallmark of these experiences.

385
01:09:09,760 --> 01:09:17,320
But anyway, at this world festival of democratic youth, or the international, whatever it was

386
01:09:17,320 --> 01:09:21,040
called, I don't have the right name for it yet.

387
01:09:21,040 --> 01:09:30,320
The idea was we got free housing and in exchange for writing up notes about what we were experiencing.

388
01:09:30,320 --> 01:09:36,480
So any panels that we went to, we had to write who was on the panel, what they said, et cetera,

389
01:09:36,480 --> 01:09:37,480
et cetera.

390
01:09:37,480 --> 01:09:40,920
And we would turn the notes in and that was again, that was why we got the free housing.

391
01:09:40,920 --> 01:09:44,840
So that was the CIA MO in that day.

392
01:09:44,840 --> 01:09:50,120
And we didn't realize that we were, we really thought that we were representing an alternate

393
01:09:50,120 --> 01:09:55,400
view of the US, that we were organizing for more freedom and democracy at home.

394
01:09:55,400 --> 01:09:59,200
And that, and because we were anti-war also, we were no testing Easter West.

395
01:09:59,200 --> 01:10:04,920
In fact, I went to a demonstration in the main square in Helsinki, where, with, which was

396
01:10:04,920 --> 01:10:09,040
a no testing Easter West demonstration, and people had signs, and the people with the signs

397
01:10:09,040 --> 01:10:14,320
were beaten, had the should be, out of them by the Helsinki police, because that was a

398
01:10:14,320 --> 01:10:16,440
communist control country at the time.

399
01:10:16,440 --> 01:10:20,120
So those people were like just demolished right in front of me.

400
01:10:20,120 --> 01:10:24,440
I'm like, oh my gosh, you know, this is an international, this is an example of what happens

401
01:10:24,440 --> 01:10:28,400
internationally when, when you're taking a stand.

402
01:10:28,400 --> 01:10:31,800
It's different from the, from the establishments.

403
01:10:31,800 --> 01:10:37,720
So you did some of that background on SDS and what you were doing in response to my question

404
01:10:37,720 --> 01:10:40,480
about why you pursued SNCC and stuff like that?

405
01:10:40,480 --> 01:10:43,000
Yeah, oh, but I didn't finish the answer.

406
01:10:43,000 --> 01:10:50,320
The answer was because in SDS, I really was a well flower, and I was, you know, as a woman

407
01:10:50,320 --> 01:10:58,000
and I wasn't, I don't think I was respected or encouraged or, or affirmed.

408
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:03,920
I was an awe of the men and the, they are intellect and their conversation and so on, but

409
01:11:03,920 --> 01:11:05,840
I wasn't affirmed in that space.

410
01:11:05,840 --> 01:11:11,840
So in the SNCC space, because I could take initiative, because I could rise to the occasion,

411
01:11:11,840 --> 01:11:18,760
I could, I could do something concrete, and I got affirmed by Jim Foreman and by Casey

412
01:11:18,840 --> 01:11:23,320
that I was doing a good thing and that I was needed and necessary and important.

413
01:11:23,320 --> 01:11:27,880
And, and that was probably one of the reasons, maybe they had in mind that they would recruit

414
01:11:27,880 --> 01:11:32,360
me to come south and I should come to the Howard meeting so they could check me out further,

415
01:11:32,360 --> 01:11:37,600
but I knew Casey from SDS circles and that may have been one of the reasons that Casey left

416
01:11:37,600 --> 01:11:44,120
SDS as well, although I know that she split from Tom, so that may have been part of it as

417
01:11:44,120 --> 01:11:51,080
well, but she was Southern and so this Nick experience fit more with her perspective

418
01:11:51,080 --> 01:11:52,680
about the world.

419
01:11:52,680 --> 01:12:00,440
So, but that's kind of it and the nutshell is affirmation and the kind of the knowing

420
01:12:00,440 --> 01:12:05,400
that you could, and then also, SNCC was much more dynamic at the time.

421
01:12:05,400 --> 01:12:08,880
I mean, SDS, we were in our heads all the time.

422
01:12:08,880 --> 01:12:12,880
We weren't doing any action, there were no real organizing campaigns, unless you were on

423
01:12:12,880 --> 01:12:19,600
a campus, like some of the campus newspapers got censored because they were writing radical

424
01:12:19,600 --> 01:12:21,200
things, all of those kinds.

425
01:12:21,200 --> 01:12:26,440
And so, if you were on a campus and you work with SDS and there were political parties,

426
01:12:26,440 --> 01:12:31,280
there was toxin, there was, I forget the mission, there was slate in California and there

427
01:12:31,280 --> 01:12:37,280
was another one in Michigan's campus that were running radical students for student government

428
01:12:37,280 --> 01:12:38,520
office and that kind of thing.

429
01:12:38,520 --> 01:12:45,520
So those would have been exciting campaigns to be involved in, but I think the fact that

430
01:12:45,520 --> 01:12:52,040
I was affirmed in the fact that I could really make a contribution with the fundraising

431
01:12:52,040 --> 01:12:56,120
and they organized in the political organizing.

432
01:12:56,120 --> 01:12:57,120
So I went south.

433
01:12:57,120 --> 01:13:01,960
I haven't really made a study of SDS before, and I've looked at some of the documents here

434
01:13:01,960 --> 01:13:02,960
and there.

435
01:13:02,960 --> 01:13:08,880
I have a sense that it was a little more male than Smith was.

436
01:13:08,880 --> 01:13:09,880
Very much more male.

437
01:13:09,880 --> 01:13:11,480
Oh, way more male.

438
01:13:11,480 --> 01:13:12,480
I mean, I think.

439
01:13:12,480 --> 01:13:17,480
Now, I don't know about the chapters on the campuses, but I think very often, in fact,

440
01:13:17,480 --> 01:13:23,080
I see it being recreated now in the student movement is when, sometimes when there are

441
01:13:23,080 --> 01:13:29,560
organizations that are headed by males, the women involved are the partners of the men.

442
01:13:29,560 --> 01:13:31,840
So in SDS, that was another thing.

443
01:13:31,840 --> 01:13:34,880
Is the women involved were partners with the men?

444
01:13:34,880 --> 01:13:36,520
So that was how they got involved.

445
01:13:36,520 --> 01:13:41,840
They didn't necessarily get involved because they had some independent presence and independent

446
01:13:41,840 --> 01:13:43,240
organizing thrust.

447
01:13:43,240 --> 01:13:50,160
And again, that was because of the day, although even now I'm seeing it, I'm seeing it recreated

448
01:13:50,160 --> 01:13:52,000
in some of the organizations.

449
01:13:52,000 --> 01:13:53,000
It is.

450
01:13:53,000 --> 01:13:54,000
It is.

451
01:13:54,000 --> 01:13:57,120
And I think they're struggling more with it.

452
01:13:57,120 --> 01:14:02,400
I mean, I think people are aware enough that they're saying, hey, wait, look at the way

453
01:14:02,400 --> 01:14:04,600
you're organized, you got to deal with this.

454
01:14:04,600 --> 01:14:11,440
And of course, that's interesting because Casey was an activist in her own right exactly.

455
01:14:11,440 --> 01:14:13,440
And her own right exactly.

456
01:14:13,440 --> 01:14:16,440
And some of the other women, exactly, exactly.

457
01:14:16,440 --> 01:14:17,440
Yeah.

458
01:14:17,440 --> 01:14:21,120
So you come south to the Atlanta office in March.

459
01:14:21,120 --> 01:14:26,920
And if I understand the chronology right, Casey is sort of the first northern coordinator

460
01:14:26,920 --> 01:14:27,920
exactly.

461
01:14:27,920 --> 01:14:28,920
And then Dinky.

462
01:14:28,920 --> 01:14:29,920
Exactly.

463
01:14:29,920 --> 01:14:31,320
Romely picks it up.

464
01:14:31,320 --> 01:14:32,320
Exactly.

465
01:14:32,320 --> 01:14:34,440
And she goes back to New York, I think.

466
01:14:34,440 --> 01:14:36,240
She goes back to New York.

467
01:14:36,240 --> 01:14:38,240
No, I don't replace her right away.

468
01:14:38,240 --> 01:14:44,080
When I come to SNCC in March of 64, Dinky is the Northern Coordinator.

469
01:14:44,080 --> 01:14:45,080
We work together.

470
01:14:45,080 --> 01:14:48,120
I go to Mississippi for the summer.

471
01:14:48,120 --> 01:14:54,320
So I'm the lead Northern Coordinator in the Greenwood office during summer 64.

472
01:14:54,320 --> 01:14:57,280
And Dotti and Judy are there, both also working.

473
01:14:57,280 --> 01:15:00,960
They work on the press stuff primarily.

474
01:15:00,960 --> 01:15:08,520
And then in the fall of 64, Dotti's owner and Judy.

475
01:15:08,520 --> 01:15:12,160
Judy Richards, since I'm sorry.

476
01:15:12,160 --> 01:15:16,920
And so this is part of SNCC kind of relocates the national office.

477
01:15:16,920 --> 01:15:17,920
Exactly.

478
01:15:17,920 --> 01:15:18,920
And the Greenwood office is the summer.

479
01:15:18,920 --> 01:15:19,920
During Freedom Summer.

480
01:15:19,920 --> 01:15:27,240
It's SNCC making a statement about its commitment to the Freedom Summer organizing.

481
01:15:27,240 --> 01:15:29,440
And so it opens an office in Greenwood.

482
01:15:29,440 --> 01:15:35,400
And it picks Greenwood as the Delta because that's the place where there are the least

483
01:15:35,400 --> 01:15:40,960
number of people, black people voting and where the heaviest oppression in the state of Mississippi

484
01:15:40,960 --> 01:15:45,520
or one of the places where the heaviest oppression happens in the Delta, which is, or the black,

485
01:15:45,520 --> 01:15:47,440
it's part of the black belt of the South.

486
01:15:47,440 --> 01:15:52,640
You started to jump to fall 64, were you going to sort of go on to what you were doing then?

487
01:15:52,640 --> 01:15:56,440
No, fall 64 is when Dinky Romney moves to New York.

488
01:15:56,440 --> 01:15:58,160
And I become the Northern Coordinator.

489
01:15:58,160 --> 01:16:03,320
I had to get the title of Northern Coordinator or Title.

490
01:16:03,320 --> 01:16:08,480
So can you describe for us what the Atlanta office was like when you come and sort of what

491
01:16:08,480 --> 01:16:09,480
you remember about it?

492
01:16:09,480 --> 01:16:10,480
Okay.

493
01:16:10,480 --> 01:16:11,800
I'm working on it.

494
01:16:11,800 --> 01:16:12,800
Right.

495
01:16:12,800 --> 01:16:13,800
So okay.

496
01:16:13,800 --> 01:16:14,800
So I come in March of 64.

497
01:16:14,800 --> 01:16:23,040
I find a group of people that are working really hard that are absolutely dedicated.

498
01:16:23,040 --> 01:16:30,360
All the things that I imagined, like people working in solidarity, in camaraderie, form

499
01:16:30,360 --> 01:16:37,720
and sweeping, form and having us pick up and kind of like organizing us to make a family

500
01:16:37,720 --> 01:16:41,720
out of this space.

501
01:16:41,720 --> 01:16:50,360
A number of people that I got to be friends with, the people who are the, you know, the

502
01:16:50,360 --> 01:16:51,360
bottom.

503
01:16:51,360 --> 01:16:53,640
I don't want to say the bottom layer because that's not really true.

504
01:16:53,640 --> 01:16:59,400
But the people who were not the big names, the Jim Formans and the John Lewis, of course

505
01:16:59,400 --> 01:17:00,400
you get to know them.

506
01:17:00,400 --> 01:17:06,480
And you sit with them and you break bread with them and that kind of thing.

507
01:17:06,480 --> 01:17:13,960
But the people that I remember are like Wilson Brown and McCray and people that like Wilson

508
01:17:13,960 --> 01:17:18,760
Brown and McCray were running the printing press and they were doing, they were doing

509
01:17:18,760 --> 01:17:19,760
Willie McCray.

510
01:17:19,760 --> 01:17:28,400
They were doing, you know, more, they were doing the support functions in the office as I

511
01:17:28,400 --> 01:17:29,400
was when I first came.

512
01:17:29,400 --> 01:17:33,000
Of course, I was a support person.

513
01:17:33,000 --> 01:17:41,160
And so, yeah, so you build these friendships and these, have these conversations about,

514
01:17:41,160 --> 01:17:44,200
I don't know, it's an interesting thing reflecting back.

515
01:17:44,200 --> 01:17:48,600
We didn't really have conversations too much about how we grew up or what we were doing

516
01:17:48,600 --> 01:17:49,600
before we got there.

517
01:17:49,600 --> 01:17:56,680
I guess we kind of talked about the work and what was happening in the field every morning.

518
01:17:56,680 --> 01:18:00,920
Someone would call all the projects, all the SNCC projects because we had a watch line,

519
01:18:00,920 --> 01:18:06,480
a wide area telephone line and it was kind of like an 800 number of today.

520
01:18:06,480 --> 01:18:11,640
So we would document every morning and every evening we would call all the projects and

521
01:18:11,640 --> 01:18:13,640
find out what had been going on.

522
01:18:13,640 --> 01:18:17,680
And then we also, another thing we had to do because we had this watch line, we paid,

523
01:18:17,680 --> 01:18:21,760
I don't know, $400 a month or something like that.

524
01:18:21,760 --> 01:18:24,400
Maybe it wasn't that much.

525
01:18:24,400 --> 01:18:28,720
To have it, then the projects would call us collect.

526
01:18:28,720 --> 01:18:35,080
And we would say, so say somebody from Greenwood would call and they would say, this is Stokely

527
01:18:35,080 --> 01:18:40,280
Carmichael and I want to talk to Jim Foreman and we would say, well, Jim Foreman's not

528
01:18:40,280 --> 01:18:41,280
here.

529
01:18:41,280 --> 01:18:43,920
So can we take an, used to leave an operator number.

530
01:18:43,920 --> 01:18:49,480
So operator 54 in Greenwood, so you could call back and get the, so we would just know

531
01:18:49,480 --> 01:18:54,360
that it was Stokely on the other end and then we would dial the, using the 800 number,

532
01:18:54,360 --> 01:18:59,720
we would dial the SNCC office number and talk to Stokely or whoever it was that had

533
01:18:59,720 --> 01:19:00,720
called.

534
01:19:00,720 --> 01:19:06,440
So that was the way we avoided the phone company charges, right?

535
01:19:06,440 --> 01:19:08,680
So I'm ready.

536
01:19:08,680 --> 01:19:10,080
I'm ready.

537
01:19:10,080 --> 01:19:14,280
Where did you live when you moved to Atlanta?

538
01:19:14,280 --> 01:19:16,840
Oh gosh, that's a really good question.

539
01:19:16,840 --> 01:19:19,840
But we do have to go back and do Southern Student Freedom Fund.

540
01:19:19,840 --> 01:19:24,800
Why don't you tell us about what the Southern Student Freedom Fund was?

541
01:19:24,800 --> 01:19:25,800
Okay.

542
01:19:25,800 --> 01:19:26,800
Okay.

543
01:19:26,800 --> 01:19:35,120
So the Southern Student Freedom Fund was organized by NSA, Young Christian students, SDS,

544
01:19:35,120 --> 01:19:38,880
and one other organization, Northern Student Movement.

545
01:19:38,880 --> 01:19:43,920
So it was four organizations of students and NSA was part of it too.

546
01:19:43,920 --> 01:19:45,720
I don't know if I said that.

547
01:19:45,720 --> 01:19:46,720
Yeah.

548
01:19:46,720 --> 01:19:47,720
Okay.

549
01:19:47,720 --> 01:19:57,320
Those four organizations organized nationally on campuses to do support work for the Southern

550
01:19:57,320 --> 01:19:59,480
Freedom Movement.

551
01:19:59,480 --> 01:20:05,640
And if I remember correctly, I think their first impetus was to raise money for scholarships

552
01:20:05,640 --> 01:20:08,520
for students who were kicked out of school.

553
01:20:08,520 --> 01:20:09,520
Yes.

554
01:20:09,520 --> 01:20:10,520
Yes.

555
01:20:10,520 --> 01:20:13,920
And then there would have been money raised for bail and there would have been money raised

556
01:20:13,920 --> 01:20:19,960
to just ascend to SNCC directly for organizing, for field secretaries and that kind of thing.

557
01:20:19,960 --> 01:20:20,960
Yeah.

558
01:20:20,960 --> 01:20:24,800
And was there anything particularly you wanted to say about their role or your connection?

559
01:20:24,800 --> 01:20:27,560
Well, I know that I think Tim was very active in that.

560
01:20:27,560 --> 01:20:31,000
Tim Jenkins was active in the Southern Student Freedom Fund.

561
01:20:31,000 --> 01:20:33,040
There was a young man from New Orleans.

562
01:20:33,040 --> 01:20:35,560
I think his name was Walter Williams maybe.

563
01:20:35,560 --> 01:20:41,960
He might have been the Jackson State student who was kicked out, right?

564
01:20:41,960 --> 01:20:46,600
He was a student who then became the coordinator of the Southern Student Freedom Fund.

565
01:20:46,600 --> 01:20:54,240
So again, it was another constellation of student energy that was developed and where black

566
01:20:54,240 --> 01:21:01,720
students played a really critical role in moving the work forward, in traveling nationally,

567
01:21:01,720 --> 01:21:05,440
in calling people in to do the work.

568
01:21:05,440 --> 01:21:08,800
So there, I want to come back to the living situation at Atlanta.

569
01:21:08,800 --> 01:21:09,800
Yes.

570
01:21:10,800 --> 01:21:16,120
Is there a sense in these networks that you're participating in that black students are

571
01:21:16,120 --> 01:21:17,640
sort of the driving force?

572
01:21:17,640 --> 01:21:18,640
Absolutely.

573
01:21:18,640 --> 01:21:19,640
Absolutely.

574
01:21:19,640 --> 01:21:22,960
I mean, this is definitely a movement that is led by black students.

575
01:21:22,960 --> 01:21:30,480
And we are, all of us are, first of all, exhilarated by the leadership of black students,

576
01:21:30,480 --> 01:21:38,800
the vision, the clarity, the dedication and the understanding of the need to fight against

577
01:21:38,800 --> 01:21:40,600
racial oppression.

578
01:21:40,600 --> 01:21:46,880
And then, because these amazing black students are leading it and in the trenches and sacrificing

579
01:21:46,880 --> 01:21:49,880
their lives in a way that we aren't sacrificing our lives.

580
01:21:49,880 --> 01:21:56,000
I mean, one of the privileges I had, of course, was when I went south to SNCC, I could leave.

581
01:21:56,000 --> 01:21:57,320
I was a Northerner.

582
01:21:57,320 --> 01:21:59,800
I had a college degree.

583
01:21:59,800 --> 01:22:07,840
I certainly had a privilege to go back to, not that I did, but to go back to, to go back

584
01:22:07,840 --> 01:22:11,960
to kind of a professional or a middle-class existence.

585
01:22:11,960 --> 01:22:16,960
And a lot of the black students had dropped out of college or been, or been expelled from

586
01:22:16,960 --> 01:22:17,960
college.

587
01:22:17,960 --> 01:22:20,240
And they were first in their families to go to college.

588
01:22:20,240 --> 01:22:25,160
And so their families' hopes were riding on their success.

589
01:22:25,160 --> 01:22:30,120
And so they had to fly in the face of their families' expectations of what they would

590
01:22:30,120 --> 01:22:32,120
do with their lives.

591
01:22:32,120 --> 01:22:39,880
Which print, which one I didn't make, sort of, how was your family reacting?

592
01:22:39,880 --> 01:22:43,000
Oh my gosh, so they were very, they were outraged.

593
01:22:43,000 --> 01:22:44,760
They did not want me in the south.

594
01:22:44,760 --> 01:22:46,320
They thought I was duked.

595
01:22:46,320 --> 01:22:50,640
They thought I was, I don't know, they thought I was crazy.

596
01:22:50,640 --> 01:22:58,000
I mean, they were always, you know, leaning on me to come home, get out of there.

597
01:22:58,000 --> 01:23:03,480
They really did think I was brainwashed and that I was under the grip of some ideological

598
01:23:03,480 --> 01:23:08,640
sinister, ideological thing.

599
01:23:08,640 --> 01:23:09,640
I don't know what they thought.

600
01:23:09,640 --> 01:23:12,000
Something was planted in my brain.

601
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:16,120
And that was making me do these crazy things, but they were not happy at all.

602
01:23:16,120 --> 01:23:17,120
Not happy.

603
01:23:17,120 --> 01:23:19,800
What about your brother?

604
01:23:19,800 --> 01:23:27,560
I don't remember him having much, I don't remember him saying much in those days.

605
01:23:27,560 --> 01:23:31,720
I know that in retrospect he's very proud of the work that I did.

606
01:23:31,720 --> 01:23:35,280
He was very supportive later on.

607
01:23:35,280 --> 01:23:40,320
He's a good thinker, a progressive thinker himself.

608
01:23:40,320 --> 01:23:42,360
Yeah, so he was supportive.

609
01:23:42,360 --> 01:23:44,360
He was never, you know.

610
01:23:44,360 --> 01:23:51,080
I can't remember the details now, but I've seen a letter that Judy Richardson wrote to

611
01:23:51,080 --> 01:23:52,080
your mother.

612
01:23:52,080 --> 01:23:53,080
Yes.

613
01:23:53,080 --> 01:23:55,120
I was not know, thanking her.

614
01:23:55,120 --> 01:23:57,280
What they did when I was in Mississippi.

615
01:23:57,280 --> 01:24:02,520
That was the intense part that they thought that was the dooping, brainwashing.

616
01:24:02,520 --> 01:24:08,560
And so I think when I was active in raising money and that kind of thing, they didn't have

617
01:24:08,560 --> 01:24:13,120
two thoughts about that because I was in Berkeley, I was safe.

618
01:24:13,120 --> 01:24:14,760
You know, I wasn't in the South.

619
01:24:14,760 --> 01:24:19,320
So March of 64 I go South, but then the summer in June I go to Greenwood.

620
01:24:19,320 --> 01:24:21,840
That's when the heat was put on.

621
01:24:21,840 --> 01:24:30,760
So the brainwashing, the dooping, they're going to deprogram me when I come home, all that

622
01:24:30,760 --> 01:24:33,640
stuff happens in the summer of 64.

623
01:24:33,640 --> 01:24:39,680
But at the same time they send us an air conditioner because they find out that we're living in

624
01:24:39,680 --> 01:24:42,440
90 degree, 100 degree heat.

625
01:24:42,440 --> 01:24:44,640
So they send us an air conditioner for the office.

626
01:24:44,640 --> 01:24:51,320
So that's kind of the contradiction of the parent who's anxious about their child's

627
01:24:51,320 --> 01:24:56,320
existence and their political thinking, but at the same time you want their kid to become

628
01:24:56,320 --> 01:24:57,320
football, right?

629
01:24:57,320 --> 01:24:59,320
So it's so bizarre.

630
01:24:59,320 --> 01:25:01,320
It's so up in middle class.

631
01:25:01,320 --> 01:25:02,320
It's ridiculous.

632
01:25:02,320 --> 01:25:03,880
Anyway, so they send us an air conditioner.

633
01:25:03,880 --> 01:25:05,080
Judy writes them a letter.

634
01:25:05,080 --> 01:25:09,160
Judy Richardson writes them a letter thanking them for the air conditioner.

635
01:25:09,160 --> 01:25:17,520
Do they have, I mean obviously they think you're crazy to go to Mississippi.

636
01:25:17,520 --> 01:25:23,000
What were their political views on segregation and the movement in general?

637
01:25:23,000 --> 01:25:33,720
Well, I think, I think because of my mother's prejudices that she's probably, I don't really

638
01:25:33,720 --> 01:25:36,720
know because I didn't have much connection with them.

639
01:25:36,720 --> 01:25:42,920
So I don't really know as the movement evolves and as more and more images are shown on TV,

640
01:25:42,920 --> 01:25:51,520
but I'm sure because of her prejudices, she's not thinking freedom movement, liberation.

641
01:25:51,520 --> 01:25:56,120
She's not thinking the things I'm thinking about why the movement is important.

642
01:25:56,120 --> 01:26:01,960
So you started to describe your living situation in Atlanta.

643
01:26:01,960 --> 01:26:08,880
So I live out, I can't remember the name of the street, but it's way out and it's kind

644
01:26:08,880 --> 01:26:09,880
of a freedom house.

645
01:26:09,880 --> 01:26:16,400
There's five or ten people living in the apartment and every morning we come into the office

646
01:26:16,400 --> 01:26:20,120
at on Raymond Street and then every evening we go out.

647
01:26:20,120 --> 01:26:24,280
We don't have transportation or cars so you got to worry if to leave when somebody who has

648
01:26:24,280 --> 01:26:29,960
a car is leaving or a cop arrived with somebody who has a car type of thing.

649
01:26:29,960 --> 01:26:41,840
And I think I lived there for, that I lived there until I may have lived there.

650
01:26:41,840 --> 01:26:48,440
I don't remember, but maybe I moved somewhere else to an apartment and then after the summer

651
01:26:48,440 --> 01:26:57,360
of 64 I lived in a house on West Anthony Street with Joyce Brown, Carol Merritt and one

652
01:26:57,360 --> 01:26:58,720
other woman.

653
01:26:58,720 --> 01:27:06,120
Joyce Brown, Carol Merritt, myself and one other woman, all three were African American

654
01:27:06,120 --> 01:27:11,120
women and we had a nice little house with four bedrooms and...

655
01:27:11,120 --> 01:27:21,960
I don't think it was Jimmy Breaker.

656
01:27:22,960 --> 01:27:26,960
Oh, it was Shirley Cooks.

657
01:27:26,960 --> 01:27:28,960
Yeah, that's who it was.

658
01:27:28,960 --> 01:27:40,480
Before we talk about that situation, the freedom house that you first moved into, is that

659
01:27:40,480 --> 01:27:43,080
a multiracial pool?

660
01:27:43,080 --> 01:27:50,760
It is and it's an apartment complex and I can't remember the name of the street, but it's

661
01:27:50,760 --> 01:27:51,760
kind of far out.

662
01:27:51,760 --> 01:27:52,760
So, yeah.

663
01:27:52,760 --> 01:27:58,360
Because I know some of the white women who first moved to Atlanta, one of the things that

664
01:27:58,360 --> 01:28:04,040
they're struggling with is that Atlanta is so segregated that some of them initially

665
01:28:04,040 --> 01:28:06,040
are living in a white world.

666
01:28:06,040 --> 01:28:07,040
In a white world, yeah.

667
01:28:07,040 --> 01:28:12,040
And then others make a move into a black world where they end up being, I think, more

668
01:28:12,040 --> 01:28:17,040
comfortable, but I don't know what you're wondering about that because you've got,

669
01:28:17,040 --> 01:28:20,320
Nick is trying to deal with an integrated...

670
01:28:20,320 --> 01:28:21,320
Exactly.

671
01:28:21,320 --> 01:28:23,320
And it's integrated exactly.

672
01:28:23,320 --> 01:28:26,120
It's segregated, exactly, exactly.

673
01:28:26,120 --> 01:28:34,080
So the place that I lived out this highway and I'll think of, I want to say, I can't

674
01:28:34,080 --> 01:28:35,560
remember the name of the highway.

675
01:28:35,560 --> 01:28:40,520
Anyway, that was not only multiracial, it was multi-gender.

676
01:28:40,520 --> 01:28:43,000
So I don't think it was just women.

677
01:28:43,000 --> 01:28:44,000
And I don't remember.

678
01:28:44,000 --> 01:28:46,920
I think I didn't stay there that long.

679
01:28:46,920 --> 01:28:50,200
And then I think I moved in with Dinky maybe.

680
01:28:50,200 --> 01:28:55,560
I think I lived, it was on English Avenue, but I'm not positive about that either, but

681
01:28:55,560 --> 01:28:58,920
I can remember walking from that apartment.

682
01:28:58,920 --> 01:29:05,760
First, when you lived out this far away highway, you had to get a ride or be driven or, you

683
01:29:05,760 --> 01:29:10,160
know, maybe we could take a bus in the morning in the daytime.

684
01:29:10,160 --> 01:29:13,760
But that was definitely a black apartment complex.

685
01:29:13,760 --> 01:29:17,760
And then this other apartment that I lived in was close enough to the office that I could

686
01:29:17,760 --> 01:29:23,520
walk because I remember walking down Raymond Street to the office every morning.

687
01:29:23,520 --> 01:29:26,960
So I'm not quite sure what that situation was.

688
01:29:26,960 --> 01:29:31,760
Do you remember whether you paid the rent or whether you're a snake paid the rent?

689
01:29:31,760 --> 01:29:39,520
I think snake paid the rent on those places, those early places up to summer of 64.

690
01:29:39,520 --> 01:29:46,800
And then fall of 64 when we moved to West Anthony Street, I think we paid the rent.

691
01:29:46,800 --> 01:29:47,800
And it was reasonable.

692
01:29:47,800 --> 01:29:50,680
I mean, we were, this isn't an interesting piece.

693
01:29:50,680 --> 01:29:53,680
I'm sure other snake folks have talked about this.

694
01:29:53,680 --> 01:30:01,680
The pay that we received was $10 a week or $9.64 after taxes.

695
01:30:01,680 --> 01:30:07,440
And basically when you were in the field, you had a free place, I'm quotes around free,

696
01:30:07,440 --> 01:30:11,920
you had a free place to stay either a freedom house or with a family.

697
01:30:11,920 --> 01:30:14,680
So the $9.64 was kind of your subsistence.

698
01:30:14,680 --> 01:30:19,760
So you were used to buy groceries or you used to buy cigarettes, which was most of a smoke

699
01:30:19,760 --> 01:30:24,320
in the day.

700
01:30:24,320 --> 01:30:28,280
Cigarettes were only $0.20 a pack or $0.15 a pack in that day.

701
01:30:28,280 --> 01:30:31,720
So you could buy your cigarettes on that.

702
01:30:31,720 --> 01:30:33,400
There's a lot of cigarettes.

703
01:30:33,400 --> 01:30:40,120
When I quit smoking in 1969, a carton was $2.10.

704
01:30:40,120 --> 01:30:46,920
So I can remember the sign on T Street in Washington, DC, cartons, 210.

705
01:30:46,920 --> 01:30:51,280
So it was pretty accessible, that smoking.

706
01:30:51,280 --> 01:30:55,120
But anyway, so I think in some cases, snake paid the rent.

707
01:30:55,120 --> 01:30:57,680
In some cases, we paid the rent.

708
01:30:57,680 --> 01:31:01,440
And then when you lived in Atlanta, your pay was $40 a week.

709
01:31:01,440 --> 01:31:04,560
And that was to acknowledge the fact that you had to pay rent.

710
01:31:04,560 --> 01:31:07,160
You had to pay utilities and that kind of thing.

711
01:31:07,160 --> 01:31:11,360
Yeah, there are interesting discussions in some of the snake minutes about paid.

712
01:31:11,360 --> 01:31:12,360
I'm sure.

713
01:31:12,360 --> 01:31:13,200
I'm sure.

714
01:31:13,200 --> 01:31:15,200
Yeah.

715
01:31:15,200 --> 01:31:19,120
So what was your work as Northern Coordinator?

716
01:31:19,120 --> 01:31:25,360
OK, well, so it depended upon, OK, so there were a number of pieces to it.

717
01:31:25,360 --> 01:31:30,360
One was writing thank you letters to the people that sent us money.

718
01:31:30,360 --> 01:31:32,840
And often we received money on solicited.

719
01:31:32,840 --> 01:31:41,360
People would send a check for $10 or $100 or $1,000 or $50.

720
01:31:41,360 --> 01:31:45,800
So we would write a handwritten thank you note to everybody.

721
01:31:45,800 --> 01:31:50,440
Another part of the work was coordinating the Friends of Snick activities.

722
01:31:50,440 --> 01:31:54,320
So not only did we call all of the projects every morning,

723
01:31:54,320 --> 01:31:57,040
we called all the Friends of Snick offices every day.

724
01:31:57,040 --> 01:32:00,160
And we would give them a report on what had happened in Macomb,

725
01:32:00,160 --> 01:32:02,960
what had happened in Greenwood, what had happened in Albany,

726
01:32:02,960 --> 01:32:04,640
what had happened in Selma.

727
01:32:04,640 --> 01:32:10,080
And then we would, if we had some kind of a request,

728
01:32:10,080 --> 01:32:15,400
like call the newspapers or call your congressman or call the White House

729
01:32:15,400 --> 01:32:21,680
or call the Justice Department or call the FBI or have a rally at such office,

730
01:32:21,680 --> 01:32:25,360
have a rally at a federal building to highlight these issues.

731
01:32:25,360 --> 01:32:29,200
And so people would organize things and go with their picket signs

732
01:32:29,200 --> 01:32:31,160
and their message.

733
01:32:31,160 --> 01:32:34,040
I mean, we did, it's so interesting of today,

734
01:32:34,040 --> 01:32:38,000
there's all this science of how do you develop the message in organizing

735
01:32:38,000 --> 01:32:40,840
and how do you change the narrative and that kind of thing.

736
01:32:40,840 --> 01:32:43,760
We had no science behind any of that.

737
01:32:43,760 --> 01:32:47,240
We just, we were out there with our messages.

738
01:32:47,240 --> 01:32:49,480
You know, stop this from happening.

739
01:32:49,480 --> 01:32:53,920
Stop the brutality in Greenwood or release the people

740
01:32:53,920 --> 01:32:56,800
who are in parchment, penitentiary.

741
01:32:56,800 --> 01:33:00,760
So, but we had no conversations about what was the way to play it with the media

742
01:33:00,760 --> 01:33:04,800
and how could we, how could we get a favor for our cause

743
01:33:04,800 --> 01:33:09,040
because we were just out there assuming that people were going to resonate

744
01:33:09,040 --> 01:33:12,720
with the issues and get involved.

745
01:33:12,720 --> 01:33:15,040
I was going to, before you added that last pen,

746
01:33:15,040 --> 01:33:18,720
I was going to ask, is that because you thought that the message itself would be good?

747
01:33:18,720 --> 01:33:20,120
Absolutely.

748
01:33:20,120 --> 01:33:21,360
Absolutely.

749
01:33:21,360 --> 01:33:24,400
Absolutely, absolutely.

750
01:33:24,440 --> 01:33:27,240
And the news coverage was different at the time

751
01:33:27,240 --> 01:33:32,880
because you would have these fabulous reporters, both TV and newspaper reporters

752
01:33:32,880 --> 01:33:36,560
who were writing and capturing the images.

753
01:33:36,560 --> 01:33:41,360
I mean, I guess the TV images were not that well developed until a little later,

754
01:33:41,360 --> 01:33:43,760
but certainly Claude Sitten from the New York Times

755
01:33:43,760 --> 01:33:50,760
and some of the other writers were just incredible at capturing the spirit and the energy

756
01:33:51,280 --> 01:33:56,840
and the issues, the legal and the constitutional and the political issues.

757
01:33:56,840 --> 01:34:01,840
So, I think one of the things that hasn't been written that much about is what

758
01:34:01,840 --> 01:34:07,080
Smith does accomplish through its Atlanta office, sort of through the bureaucracy.

759
01:34:07,080 --> 01:34:09,080
Right, right.

760
01:34:09,080 --> 01:34:14,080
Right, well, that was the tendency to think of us as that, yeah.

761
01:34:14,080 --> 01:34:18,680
Well, what are the kinds of work that's taking place in the Atlanta office

762
01:34:18,680 --> 01:34:21,760
when you get there in large 60s?

763
01:34:21,760 --> 01:34:28,840
So, part of the work is because we're raising the money, we're also giving the money,

764
01:34:28,840 --> 01:34:34,600
we're paying the payroll, and we're giving the money to projects for,

765
01:34:34,600 --> 01:34:40,280
to the, when I say project, I mean a particular office in a community,

766
01:34:40,280 --> 01:34:44,920
so there was the Greenwood project or the McCormon project or the Hattiesburg office.

767
01:34:45,000 --> 01:34:49,320
So, we would be giving money, distributing money to those offices.

768
01:34:49,320 --> 01:34:54,920
We would be collecting all the information and documenting all the information

769
01:34:54,920 --> 01:34:58,200
and then using that information either for lawsuits,

770
01:34:58,200 --> 01:35:08,040
for sending to the Justice Department, for, for scholars, for newspaper writers,

771
01:35:08,040 --> 01:35:08,880
for whoever.

772
01:35:08,880 --> 01:35:14,080
In other words, we're documenting the daily atrocities, the daily insults,

773
01:35:14,080 --> 01:35:18,640
the daily brutality of each community in the South.

774
01:35:18,640 --> 01:35:24,280
And then we were also working with the NNWACP Legal Defense Fund,

775
01:35:24,280 --> 01:35:28,120
with SCLC, with the Congress of Racial Equality,

776
01:35:28,120 --> 01:35:30,720
with the National Lawyers Guild,

777
01:35:30,720 --> 01:35:34,040
with the Medical Committee for Human Rights.

778
01:35:34,040 --> 01:35:38,880
So, we were working with these national organizations with a lot of the church organizations,

779
01:35:38,880 --> 01:35:43,400
even National Council of Churches or the Unitarians or the Episcopalians

780
01:35:43,400 --> 01:35:46,280
or the UCC, the United Church of Christ folks.

781
01:35:46,280 --> 01:35:51,680
We would be working, coordinating with them to think about what their role might be,

782
01:35:51,680 --> 01:35:54,120
how they might make a contribution, that kind of thing.

783
01:35:54,120 --> 01:35:59,000
So, and there were delegations that came south and that would do some learning.

784
01:35:59,000 --> 01:36:01,520
So, there were a lot of different moving pieces.

785
01:36:01,520 --> 01:36:09,760
There was supporting the field projects and the field organizing was the dominant one.

786
01:36:09,760 --> 01:36:15,640
And then the information that we sent to the Northern Friends of Snick offices,

787
01:36:15,640 --> 01:36:17,480
documented what was going on.

788
01:36:17,480 --> 01:36:23,080
And then if there was a theme to what we were trying to take care of it, that particular point in time,

789
01:36:23,080 --> 01:36:28,320
it might have been something like the agriculture, the ASCS, the agricultural,

790
01:36:28,320 --> 01:36:32,920
agricultural stabilization, conservation service.

791
01:36:32,920 --> 01:36:39,920
So, the ASCS was a federal program that enabled farmers to get some subsidies

792
01:36:39,920 --> 01:36:43,480
for either growing a certain thing or not growing a certain thing,

793
01:36:43,480 --> 01:36:48,720
but it was the white farmers who benefited from that program and not the black farmers.

794
01:36:48,720 --> 01:36:54,600
So, there was a struggle to have the black farmers included in the benefits of that program,

795
01:36:54,600 --> 01:36:56,120
the food stamp program.

796
01:36:56,120 --> 01:37:02,120
There were all of these federal programs, including the school desegregation ruling

797
01:37:02,120 --> 01:37:08,840
by the Congress, that you had a fight to make the promise of the piece of legislation

798
01:37:08,840 --> 01:37:13,800
actual, actually given some benefit to the African-American communities.

799
01:37:13,800 --> 01:37:18,840
And that's the Civil Rights Act of 64, which would go deep into the school desegregation

800
01:37:18,840 --> 01:37:19,840
of the government.

801
01:37:19,840 --> 01:37:20,680
I think it's 63, maybe?

802
01:37:20,680 --> 01:37:21,680
That doesn't know it's 64.

803
01:37:21,680 --> 01:37:22,680
Okay, you're the scholar.

804
01:37:22,680 --> 01:37:23,680
I'm just the person in the trenches, right?

805
01:37:23,680 --> 01:37:24,680
Yeah, so 64.

806
01:37:24,680 --> 01:37:25,680
So, 64.

807
01:37:25,680 --> 01:37:32,680
Yeah, so 64, that makes sense.

808
01:37:32,680 --> 01:37:38,680
So, 65 is the key voting rights, Civil Rights Act.

809
01:37:38,680 --> 01:37:46,680
Yeah, so 64, each school district was required to have a plan for desegregating.

810
01:37:46,680 --> 01:37:53,680
And of course, many school districts in the South formed their own white, white only private school system.

811
01:37:53,680 --> 01:38:00,280
So, but if you didn't do that, you were supposed to have a plan where you could have freedom

812
01:38:00,280 --> 01:38:05,680
of choice, which of course put the burden on the black family that was wanting better education

813
01:38:05,680 --> 01:38:06,680
for their kids.

814
01:38:06,680 --> 01:38:11,600
So, they had to undergo all the harassment and the attacks because they made the choice

815
01:38:11,600 --> 01:38:19,480
to send their child to the black school, or you would have some districts, very few districts,

816
01:38:19,480 --> 01:38:25,560
had all the first graders got put together, all the second graders, or maybe the first

817
01:38:25,560 --> 01:38:31,600
second and third graders got put together across racial minds and then they would continue

818
01:38:31,600 --> 01:38:32,600
on up.

819
01:38:32,600 --> 01:38:34,600
So, but that was very seldom.

820
01:38:34,600 --> 01:38:40,840
It was mostly freedom of choice and that meant that it wasn't free choice, basically.

821
01:38:40,840 --> 01:38:43,840
I want to come back to that because I think you did a lot of work on that.

822
01:38:43,840 --> 01:38:44,840
I did.

823
01:38:44,840 --> 01:38:45,840
I did.

824
01:38:45,840 --> 01:38:46,840
Okay.

825
01:38:46,840 --> 01:38:57,320
So, when you come to the Atlanta office and you're working, is there already a print shop?

826
01:38:57,320 --> 01:38:58,320
I think there is.

827
01:38:58,320 --> 01:39:03,000
Yeah, there's a print shop and we are doing, yes, we're doing publications.

828
01:39:03,000 --> 01:39:07,760
We're doing, and clearly we're doing the minigrafting, but there is some kind of a printing

829
01:39:07,760 --> 01:39:08,760
press.

830
01:39:08,760 --> 01:39:10,440
So, there's Mark Suckle.

831
01:39:10,440 --> 01:39:20,360
There's Wilson Brown, Willie McCray, and it's his other guy's name for getting his name.

832
01:39:20,360 --> 01:39:28,160
But there were some hard working folks who were doing the printing Walter Tilla, I don't

833
01:39:28,160 --> 01:39:30,400
know if he was in the printing press.

834
01:39:30,400 --> 01:39:31,400
So, anyway.

835
01:39:31,400 --> 01:39:39,080
And one of the things I've seen is that Snick takes these newspaper articles and plays

836
01:39:39,080 --> 01:39:40,080
them out with pictures.

837
01:39:40,080 --> 01:39:41,080
Yes.

838
01:39:41,080 --> 01:39:42,080
The fundraising appeal.

839
01:39:42,080 --> 01:39:43,080
Exactly.

840
01:39:43,080 --> 01:39:44,080
The student voice.

841
01:39:44,080 --> 01:39:50,880
The student voice was the publication and that was printed on the printing press.

842
01:39:50,880 --> 01:39:55,360
So, you could print an 11 by 17 piece of paper and it looked pretty nice.

843
01:39:55,360 --> 01:39:59,800
I don't know what the printing method was at the time, but it was better than the minigraf

844
01:39:59,800 --> 01:40:01,880
thing because you could have the pictures, exactly.

845
01:40:01,880 --> 01:40:07,120
Are you doing, when those things are printed, these things are printed up, you have to

846
01:40:07,120 --> 01:40:08,920
hold them and stuff.

847
01:40:08,920 --> 01:40:09,920
Absolutely.

848
01:40:09,920 --> 01:40:11,800
Yes, I'm so glad you were.

849
01:40:11,800 --> 01:40:17,720
We had so many enveloped stuffing parties and folding parties because we don't fold a machine

850
01:40:17,720 --> 01:40:20,920
or automatic automated fundraising.

851
01:40:20,920 --> 01:40:21,920
No.

852
01:40:21,920 --> 01:40:28,380
So, yes, we're up late at night folding and stuffing and talking and having pizza and playing

853
01:40:28,380 --> 01:40:31,480
music and cutting up and that type of thing.

854
01:40:31,480 --> 01:40:32,480
So that was part of...

855
01:40:32,480 --> 01:40:34,480
You're sort of college student.

856
01:40:34,480 --> 01:40:35,480
Part A.

857
01:40:35,480 --> 01:40:36,480
Exactly.

858
01:40:36,480 --> 01:40:38,160
With the envelope stuffing and so on.

859
01:40:38,160 --> 01:40:42,680
And of course, everybody knew that the fundraising was critical to the success of the organization

860
01:40:42,680 --> 01:40:45,480
and so this was something we had to do.

861
01:40:45,480 --> 01:40:47,000
So there would be a fundraising appeal.

862
01:40:47,000 --> 01:40:51,200
That was something that we did in my department was write the letter.

863
01:40:51,200 --> 01:40:57,080
And one of the things that we stayed away from was the, oh, you have to help the poor Mississippi

864
01:40:57,080 --> 01:40:59,240
person who has no rights.

865
01:40:59,240 --> 01:41:01,400
We were more, this is a democratic country.

866
01:41:01,400 --> 01:41:06,160
We need to be committed and dedicated to our ideals.

867
01:41:06,160 --> 01:41:11,280
This is an egregious violation of democratic principles and we need to...

868
01:41:11,280 --> 01:41:12,280
I mean, I'm not using...

869
01:41:12,280 --> 01:41:16,280
I didn't use egregious and those words in the fundraising appeal.

870
01:41:16,280 --> 01:41:21,840
But you know, that was the idea was that we're not being true to our better side and therefore

871
01:41:21,840 --> 01:41:23,440
we have to...

872
01:41:23,440 --> 01:41:29,160
And here are these courageous young people who are risking their lives and taking a step

873
01:41:29,160 --> 01:41:35,640
way beyond their comfort zone or anybody's comfort zone to bring the promise of democracy

874
01:41:35,640 --> 01:41:36,640
to the South.

875
01:41:36,640 --> 01:41:38,160
Of course, it was all about the South.

876
01:41:38,160 --> 01:41:44,480
We had no real lens on what the inequities in the North were and what the structural,

877
01:41:44,480 --> 01:41:49,000
certainly not understanding what the structural inequities were that were going on at the

878
01:41:49,000 --> 01:41:53,640
same time in terms of jobs and housing and education in the North.

879
01:41:54,640 --> 01:42:00,640
So I know that some of the SNCC women had a sit-in in January of 1964.

880
01:42:00,640 --> 01:42:01,640
Yes.

881
01:42:01,640 --> 01:42:04,640
You get slightly different stories depending on who you are.

882
01:42:04,640 --> 01:42:05,640
Yes.

883
01:42:05,640 --> 01:42:10,640
But when you came in and started working, did you have any awareness of that?

884
01:42:10,640 --> 01:42:11,640
Not really.

885
01:42:11,640 --> 01:42:17,960
I don't think I only knew that in retrospect when we were working on the hands on the Freedom

886
01:42:17,960 --> 01:42:24,280
Plow Book and of course Judy Richardson has it in her story and other people referred to

887
01:42:24,280 --> 01:42:25,280
it.

888
01:42:25,280 --> 01:42:26,280
Of course.

889
01:42:26,280 --> 01:42:27,280
Oh, briefly.

890
01:42:27,280 --> 01:42:28,280
Oh, briefly.

891
01:42:28,280 --> 01:42:29,280
Yes.

892
01:42:29,280 --> 01:42:30,280
Okay.

893
01:42:30,280 --> 01:42:36,880
So briefly, this is 52 stories of women who were part of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating

894
01:42:36,880 --> 01:42:40,000
Committee and it came out in 2010.

895
01:42:40,000 --> 01:42:42,240
So there were six of us who edited it.

896
01:42:42,240 --> 01:42:49,040
Judy Richardson, Doddy Zellner, Faith Hulsart, Martha Prescott Norman and Jean Smith Young

897
01:42:49,040 --> 01:42:50,040
and myself.

898
01:42:50,040 --> 01:42:51,440
And you were all SNCC women?

899
01:42:51,440 --> 01:42:52,440
We were all SNCC women.

900
01:42:52,440 --> 01:42:53,440
Yes.

901
01:42:53,440 --> 01:42:57,440
It took us 15 years to get this out into the public.

902
01:42:57,440 --> 01:43:00,440
And we all thank you for doing it.

903
01:43:00,440 --> 01:43:01,440
Yeah.

904
01:43:01,440 --> 01:43:02,440
You're very welcome.

905
01:43:02,440 --> 01:43:03,440
It was a labor of love.

906
01:43:03,440 --> 01:43:04,440
I want to say.

907
01:43:04,440 --> 01:43:05,440
I don't know.

908
01:43:05,440 --> 01:43:06,440
Okay.

909
01:43:06,440 --> 01:43:13,400
What was it like to go into the Sisypian summer 64?

910
01:43:13,400 --> 01:43:17,760
You come in actually a little bit before I asked you.

911
01:43:17,760 --> 01:43:22,640
When you were recruited, you were obviously recruited to come work in the Atlanta office.

912
01:43:22,640 --> 01:43:23,640
Absolutely.

913
01:43:23,640 --> 01:43:24,640
On your own.

914
01:43:24,640 --> 01:43:26,640
Did you have any desire to go in the field?

915
01:43:26,640 --> 01:43:27,640
Absolutely.

916
01:43:27,640 --> 01:43:28,640
Oh, yes.

917
01:43:28,640 --> 01:43:30,720
Of course, you wanted to go into the field.

918
01:43:30,720 --> 01:43:33,400
I mean, there were, I was torn.

919
01:43:33,400 --> 01:43:35,120
You know, I felt safe in the office.

920
01:43:35,120 --> 01:43:38,760
I felt this parent thing that I was dealing with, right?

921
01:43:38,760 --> 01:43:42,600
Where they were putting all this pressure on me to not be there.

922
01:43:42,600 --> 01:43:45,440
So I felt I could carve out a space in the office.

923
01:43:45,440 --> 01:43:46,440
I was competent.

924
01:43:46,440 --> 01:43:48,320
I knew the work.

925
01:43:48,320 --> 01:43:49,440
I could do it.

926
01:43:49,440 --> 01:43:50,840
You know, I was pretty efficient.

927
01:43:50,840 --> 01:43:54,200
I was pretty effective.

928
01:43:54,200 --> 01:43:55,920
But I wanted to be in the field.

929
01:43:55,920 --> 01:44:01,000
I was thrilled to go to Mississippi for the summer of 64 to be in the Greenwood office.

930
01:44:01,000 --> 01:44:04,640
And even though I was in the office then, I remember asking people, I want to go

931
01:44:04,640 --> 01:44:05,640
canvassing with you.

932
01:44:05,640 --> 01:44:06,920
I want to go out.

933
01:44:06,920 --> 01:44:11,820
And I did go canvassing with Peter Orris a couple times who was one of the white summer

934
01:44:11,820 --> 01:44:15,640
volunteers who's now in Chicago.

935
01:44:15,640 --> 01:44:20,800
He became a physician actually in Chicago and has worked for many years in, you know,

936
01:44:20,800 --> 01:44:27,040
health access and health equity organizing efforts as a doctor.

937
01:44:27,040 --> 01:44:31,920
But anyway, I went out canvassing with him a couple times to ask people to register

938
01:44:31,920 --> 01:44:32,920
to vote.

939
01:44:32,920 --> 01:44:38,000
And to get the essence of the work, I wanted to be part of that essence.

940
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:45,640
So in fact, in the fall of 65, after I had been the Northern Coordinator for a year, I

941
01:44:45,640 --> 01:44:50,480
decided I didn't want to do the Northern Coordinating anymore, but I wanted to do what

942
01:44:50,480 --> 01:44:53,480
was called federal programs.

943
01:44:53,480 --> 01:44:58,280
So federal programs had to do with what we talked about before about the discriminatory

944
01:44:58,280 --> 01:45:01,960
application of all the federal benefits in the south.

945
01:45:01,960 --> 01:45:04,840
And somebody had been doing this work.

946
01:45:04,840 --> 01:45:09,600
I can't remember if somebody had been doing it or if it had just been done in Mississippi.

947
01:45:09,600 --> 01:45:15,520
And so I imagined that I could do this by traveling to the different projects and documenting

948
01:45:15,520 --> 01:45:22,960
the inequalities of the giving out of the benefit, the federal benefits.

949
01:45:22,960 --> 01:45:28,160
And then I would also go to Washington and do some research on the actual working of

950
01:45:28,880 --> 01:45:29,720
the program.

951
01:45:29,720 --> 01:45:31,240
So it was food stamps.

952
01:45:31,240 --> 01:45:34,960
It was the school desegregation stuff.

953
01:45:34,960 --> 01:45:44,120
It was the ASCS, the agricultural stabilization, conservation service, and other kind of local

954
01:45:44,120 --> 01:45:45,880
things.

955
01:45:45,880 --> 01:45:47,200
So I did go to Arkansas.

956
01:45:47,200 --> 01:45:50,040
I went to both the projects in Little Rock and Pine Bluff.

957
01:45:50,040 --> 01:45:57,200
And I interviewed people and documented took like affidavits, which would be sworn statements

958
01:45:57,200 --> 01:46:06,920
about the discriminatory practices or the impact of these practices on the community.

959
01:46:06,920 --> 01:46:08,360
So that was one thing I did.

960
01:46:08,360 --> 01:46:15,320
And then when I got to Washington, maybe the second time I got to Washington, there was

961
01:46:15,320 --> 01:46:22,800
this issue with the school, the Civil Rights Act of 64 summer, there were, I think the

962
01:46:22,840 --> 01:46:30,360
Congress had to write some rules for how would the school districts go about desegregating.

963
01:46:30,360 --> 01:46:35,040
And so the rules maybe had been written by them.

964
01:46:35,040 --> 01:46:43,520
And then there were all of these questions about how was the act being put into practice.

965
01:46:43,520 --> 01:46:49,280
And so Mary and Barry, who was the head of the Washington DC office at the time, and I

966
01:46:49,280 --> 01:46:53,960
went to the office of education, and we asked if we could see their files, and they let

967
01:46:53,960 --> 01:46:55,640
us see their files.

968
01:46:55,640 --> 01:47:02,080
And in their files, we found these incredible pieces of information about the dispensations

969
01:47:02,080 --> 01:47:03,520
that were being given.

970
01:47:03,520 --> 01:47:08,200
A congressman would write to the office of education, he would say, well, in my school

971
01:47:08,200 --> 01:47:14,440
district in Hattiesburg, we are not ready to desegregate, and therefore we were okay

972
01:47:14,440 --> 01:47:19,240
with a freedom of choice plan for the first grade type of thing.

973
01:47:19,240 --> 01:47:23,600
So they were like the minimum step forward is what they were willing.

974
01:47:23,600 --> 01:47:28,960
And the office of education would write back, and they would say, oh, that's okay.

975
01:47:28,960 --> 01:47:32,320
You're relieved of any burden of responsibility.

976
01:47:32,320 --> 01:47:34,840
So what we did is we documented all of that.

977
01:47:34,840 --> 01:47:40,920
We put it together in a report, which we published, it was a minute of graph, because I remember

978
01:47:40,920 --> 01:47:42,640
what it looked like.

979
01:47:42,720 --> 01:47:51,280
And we had a big press conference in November, I think, of 65, maybe where John Lewis came,

980
01:47:51,280 --> 01:47:54,320
and we presented this data to the press.

981
01:47:54,320 --> 01:48:00,480
Now what impact it had, I guess we never figured out whether the report itself, but it's

982
01:48:00,480 --> 01:48:03,440
like a lot of different iterations today.

983
01:48:03,440 --> 01:48:10,320
Somebody will do a report about access to jobs being inequitable, or they'll do affordable

984
01:48:10,320 --> 01:48:14,320
housing or whatever, so you'd make a big fanfare you presented to the press, the press

985
01:48:14,320 --> 01:48:21,160
writes about it, and then it's available for other scholars and researchers and congressmen

986
01:48:21,160 --> 01:48:26,480
and lawmakers who will then go on to write a different piece of legislation that takes

987
01:48:26,480 --> 01:48:28,960
into account what the findings have been.

988
01:48:28,960 --> 01:48:33,280
So I want to circle back to a couple of other things that you talked about.

989
01:48:33,280 --> 01:48:34,280
Okay.

990
01:48:34,280 --> 01:48:38,520
I think one thing that people might found useful, I think what the Civil Rights Act did was

991
01:48:38,520 --> 01:48:43,120
it gave the federal government the power to withdraw federal funding.

992
01:48:43,120 --> 01:48:44,120
Exactly.

993
01:48:44,120 --> 01:48:45,120
Exactly.

994
01:48:45,120 --> 01:48:46,120
That was the point.

995
01:48:46,120 --> 01:48:50,400
If they didn't have the plan, and then the office of education would say, okay, your

996
01:48:50,400 --> 01:48:53,080
plan's fine, you keep the federal money, right?

997
01:48:53,080 --> 01:48:57,760
There's this period of negotiation on what they had to do to fill that in.

998
01:48:57,760 --> 01:48:58,760
Exactly.

999
01:48:58,760 --> 01:49:01,480
It became a little stronger at this time.

1000
01:49:01,480 --> 01:49:02,480
It existed.

1001
01:49:02,480 --> 01:49:05,360
You described it.

1002
01:49:05,360 --> 01:49:08,680
And also the organizing in the South, I mean, we can't forget that because there were

1003
01:49:08,680 --> 01:49:14,360
people in communities who were enrolling their children in the white school and who were

1004
01:49:14,360 --> 01:49:19,000
being thrown off the plantation, who were being kicked out of their jobs, who were being

1005
01:49:19,000 --> 01:49:22,640
harassed, who were being, has us, were being shot into.

1006
01:49:22,640 --> 01:49:25,600
So it was part of the organizing picture.

1007
01:49:25,600 --> 01:49:30,200
It became part of the next iteration of demands beyond voting rights.

1008
01:49:30,200 --> 01:49:33,560
It was the demand to have access to the federal programs.

1009
01:49:33,560 --> 01:49:36,680
It was the demand for equal education, et cetera.

1010
01:49:36,680 --> 01:49:46,520
So a lot of people see freedom somewhere as an MFEP challenge as kind of a high point,

1011
01:49:46,520 --> 01:49:51,800
and that there's a real drop off.

1012
01:49:51,800 --> 01:49:52,800
After that.

1013
01:49:52,800 --> 01:49:59,800
I think that was a very, very, very, very, very, very important thing.

1014
01:49:59,800 --> 01:50:06,800
And I think that the freedom of the MFEP challenge, and my sense is from reading your piece

1015
01:50:06,800 --> 01:50:12,800
and hands on the freedom file, that you don't, that wasn't your experience.

1016
01:50:12,800 --> 01:50:17,800
Well, I think what it did, the fact that the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party delegation

1017
01:50:17,800 --> 01:50:21,800
was not accepted wholeheartedly by the National Democratic Party.

1018
01:50:21,800 --> 01:50:27,800
But it's not just about what the picture is that we've painted of the denial of voting rights

1019
01:50:27,800 --> 01:50:32,800
to people in the South, and especially within the party structure, in this case,

1020
01:50:32,800 --> 01:50:37,800
they are not going to pay attention to that because they're more interested in their own political,

1021
01:50:37,800 --> 01:50:40,800
you know, Johnson was certainly interested in getting elected as president,

1022
01:50:40,800 --> 01:50:44,800
and he wasn't going to compromise the support of the Southern States, all of that.

1023
01:50:44,800 --> 01:50:47,800
So for us, it was a rethinking for us and Snick.

1024
01:50:47,800 --> 01:50:50,800
We're thinking of what the heck are we doing?

1025
01:50:50,800 --> 01:50:52,800
Or what's the next step?

1026
01:50:52,800 --> 01:50:58,800
Do we, as Foreman put forward, do we have a Black Belt summer project the next summer?

1027
01:50:58,800 --> 01:51:01,800
And we go into Alabama, and Arkansas, and Georgia.

1028
01:51:01,800 --> 01:51:06,800
And so we've spread across the South, South Carolina was part of that too.

1029
01:51:06,800 --> 01:51:11,800
And Jack Minnes in the research department had done all the research to show all the denial of voting rights

1030
01:51:11,800 --> 01:51:15,800
across all those Black counties, the Black Belt counties across the South.

1031
01:51:15,800 --> 01:51:17,800
Do we do that?

1032
01:51:17,800 --> 01:51:20,800
Some people that was that's more of the same, right?

1033
01:51:20,800 --> 01:51:24,800
Do we do continue the local organizing?

1034
01:51:24,800 --> 01:51:30,800
Does it become more about schools and about access to benefits and food stamps and that kind of thing?

1035
01:51:30,800 --> 01:51:33,800
Do we continue the voting rights conversation?

1036
01:51:33,800 --> 01:51:39,800
And so we continue all of that, and in fact, we never resolved the Black Belt summer project issue.

1037
01:51:39,800 --> 01:51:44,800
More students do come South in the summer of 65 to Mississippi.

1038
01:51:44,800 --> 01:51:47,800
Not that many, but some.

1039
01:51:47,800 --> 01:51:52,800
We have all these soul-searching conversations in the SNCC meetings that year.

1040
01:51:52,800 --> 01:51:58,800
We have four SNCC meetings that year, two in the fall, maybe, and two in the spring.

1041
01:51:58,800 --> 01:52:07,800
And we debate and discuss the direction of the movement, and we talk about the, I mean, all the themes were there.

1042
01:52:07,800 --> 01:52:08,800
I mean, I won't go in.

1043
01:52:08,800 --> 01:52:13,800
I'm sure somebody's interview will be able to elucidate all these points.

1044
01:52:13,800 --> 01:52:17,800
But we really do a lot of soul-searching.

1045
01:52:17,800 --> 01:52:27,800
And as young people, we try to pay attention to all of the organizational development issues,

1046
01:52:27,800 --> 01:52:31,800
like the personnel issues, how are people working?

1047
01:52:31,800 --> 01:52:33,800
Are people absent?

1048
01:52:33,800 --> 01:52:36,800
You know, are people, like, burned out?

1049
01:52:36,800 --> 01:52:38,800
And are they, therefore, not working?

1050
01:52:38,800 --> 01:52:40,800
And we're still sending them a paycheck?

1051
01:52:40,800 --> 01:52:45,800
Or are people, how are the different projects working?

1052
01:52:45,800 --> 01:52:49,800
And so we were paying attention to that.

1053
01:52:49,800 --> 01:52:54,800
And then, of course, Selma happened, which is in March of 65.

1054
01:52:54,800 --> 01:53:04,800
And then we're pushing back a little bit about that, because we're, like, not in favor of Dr. King plonking himself into a community,

1055
01:53:04,800 --> 01:53:11,800
and we're pushing for something big, but not building the capacity in the local community, not developing leadership,

1056
01:53:11,800 --> 01:53:15,800
not going at the pace that the local community wants to go at.

1057
01:53:15,800 --> 01:53:21,800
Of course, the story is that Amelia Boynton, who was the leader of the Dallas County Voters League,

1058
01:53:21,800 --> 01:53:26,800
she wanted Dr. King to come in, because she thought things were not moving quickly enough.

1059
01:53:26,800 --> 01:53:31,800
The SNCC field secretaries were building that capacity and leadership was in the community.

1060
01:53:31,800 --> 01:53:36,800
And I think they felt that Dr. King coming in was a diversion from that.

1061
01:53:36,800 --> 01:53:43,800
Of course, the SNCC field secretaries supported the Selma and Montgomery March,

1062
01:53:43,800 --> 01:53:46,800
and then, you know, the rest is documented in history.

1063
01:53:46,800 --> 01:53:48,800
I wouldn't go into that.

1064
01:53:48,800 --> 01:53:54,800
So I was only in Atlanta when the attack on the Edmund Pettis Bridge happened, and then we were able,

1065
01:53:54,800 --> 01:53:56,800
this is amazing.

1066
01:53:56,800 --> 01:54:04,800
I was able to charter a plane to send four people, I even have Donaldson,

1067
01:54:04,800 --> 01:54:08,800
Courtland Cox, and Pratia Hall, and I don't know who the fourth person was,

1068
01:54:08,800 --> 01:54:13,800
to Selma from Atlanta to get, so they could get there quickly,

1069
01:54:13,800 --> 01:54:17,800
to be kind of the backup stick support for John Lewis and John Love,

1070
01:54:17,800 --> 01:54:21,800
who was the field secretary in the community.

1071
01:54:21,800 --> 01:54:24,800
So yeah, that was kind of amazing.

1072
01:54:24,800 --> 01:54:31,800
Some of the stories of planes too walking out on the runway.

1073
01:54:31,800 --> 01:54:32,800
Yeah, exactly.

1074
01:54:32,800 --> 01:54:38,800
The other piece was the cars, the fact that we had a fleet of 40 cars called the Sojourner Motor Fleet.

1075
01:54:38,800 --> 01:54:40,800
Yeah, Sojourner Motor Fleet.

1076
01:54:40,800 --> 01:54:43,800
And who knows where that money came from.

1077
01:54:43,800 --> 01:54:47,800
I mean, I suspect it might have come from Harry Belafonte, or who knows.

1078
01:54:47,800 --> 01:54:50,800
But there was, and actually maybe it was 20 cars.

1079
01:54:50,800 --> 01:54:52,800
It was a 40 cars or 20 cars.

1080
01:54:52,800 --> 01:54:56,800
But anyway, we got a chunk of money from some source.

1081
01:54:56,800 --> 01:54:59,800
Belafonte was one of Snicks' big benefactors.

1082
01:54:59,800 --> 01:55:02,800
Also, SCLC got a lot of money from him.

1083
01:55:02,800 --> 01:55:07,800
But we were able to buy a fleet of cars, very low end fords,

1084
01:55:07,800 --> 01:55:11,800
and put CB radios in them so that people could communicate in dangerous,

1085
01:55:11,800 --> 01:55:13,800
especially in dangerous areas.

1086
01:55:13,800 --> 01:55:17,800
So each project was assigned a car.

1087
01:55:17,800 --> 01:55:18,800
And that was amazing.

1088
01:55:18,800 --> 01:55:22,800
One of the pieces of the radios that they were able to buy the cars,

1089
01:55:22,800 --> 01:55:26,800
Snickles able to buy the cars at cost, at what the price did.

1090
01:55:26,800 --> 01:55:28,800
The dealer's price?

1091
01:55:28,800 --> 01:55:31,800
Oh, because of the United Auto workers.

1092
01:55:31,800 --> 01:55:32,800
Oh, that's interesting.

1093
01:55:32,800 --> 01:55:34,800
I didn't know that part, right?

1094
01:55:34,800 --> 01:55:35,800
Yeah.

1095
01:55:35,800 --> 01:55:37,800
So they did buy a sticker price ball for that.

1096
01:55:37,800 --> 01:55:42,800
One of the histories that has never been really written is this history of money flows.

1097
01:55:42,800 --> 01:55:48,800
Like what were the resources that either SCLC, Snick, and WACP had at,

1098
01:55:48,800 --> 01:55:50,800
or Core had that their disposal?

1099
01:55:50,800 --> 01:55:52,800
How did they get it?

1100
01:55:52,800 --> 01:55:54,800
Where did they get it from?

1101
01:55:54,800 --> 01:55:55,800
That kind of thing?

1102
01:55:55,800 --> 01:55:58,800
I know in Snick there was a big debate at one point about the voting.

1103
01:55:58,800 --> 01:56:01,800
The focus on voting rights as opposed to direct action.

1104
01:56:01,800 --> 01:56:06,800
Because the big foundations were ready to give money through the voter education project.

1105
01:56:06,800 --> 01:56:10,800
And within Snick everybody thought, oh my gosh, this is going to soften the movement.

1106
01:56:10,800 --> 01:56:13,800
It's going to dampen the organizing.

1107
01:56:13,800 --> 01:56:15,800
It's going to divert people's attention.

1108
01:56:15,800 --> 01:56:24,800
And so Miss Baker was the one who suggested that Snick do both the direct action as well as the voting rights organizing.

1109
01:56:24,800 --> 01:56:30,800
And then of course the voting rights organizing turned out to be direct action because of the resistance from the Southern.

1110
01:56:30,800 --> 01:56:37,800
So the candidates thought that if they think they could...

1111
01:56:37,800 --> 01:56:40,800
Yes, yes, exactly. They thought that they could...

1112
01:56:40,800 --> 01:56:43,800
They could... they definitely did. They had no idea.

1113
01:56:43,800 --> 01:56:51,800
You mentioned a little bit ago moving from the position of the Northern coordinator to working with federal programs.

1114
01:56:51,800 --> 01:56:53,800
It was something like that.

1115
01:56:53,800 --> 01:56:59,800
So you saw a need for a different kind of work or you had...

1116
01:56:59,800 --> 01:57:04,800
So do you just propose and say, hey, I want to do this and then you make that move?

1117
01:57:04,800 --> 01:57:06,800
How did something like that happen?

1118
01:57:06,800 --> 01:57:09,800
Well, I proposed it and then I got agreement.

1119
01:57:09,800 --> 01:57:11,800
I mean, I guess I proposed it to the executive committee.

1120
01:57:11,800 --> 01:57:16,800
I'm not quite sure whether that's what I did.

1121
01:57:16,800 --> 01:57:19,800
And then I think what happens...

1122
01:57:19,800 --> 01:57:22,800
So I get the approval to do this federal programs work.

1123
01:57:22,800 --> 01:57:24,800
I don't think I had much guidance.

1124
01:57:24,800 --> 01:57:26,800
And I don't think...

1125
01:57:26,800 --> 01:57:31,800
And it was part of the more loose structure of Snick,

1126
01:57:31,800 --> 01:57:37,800
which enabled people to carve out a space for themselves if they thought, oh, here's a space I can do.

1127
01:57:37,800 --> 01:57:42,800
And you would normally get approval to do it.

1128
01:57:42,800 --> 01:57:45,800
On some level, I had to do with white privilege, though, I think,

1129
01:57:45,800 --> 01:57:50,800
because as a white staff person, as somebody who had these...

1130
01:57:50,800 --> 01:57:56,800
It wasn't that it was a Snick strategy to go after the documenting of the federal programs.

1131
01:57:56,800 --> 01:58:00,800
There was a strategy to do the congressional challenge at the time,

1132
01:58:00,800 --> 01:58:03,800
post-64 convention.

1133
01:58:03,800 --> 01:58:05,800
And there was...

1134
01:58:05,800 --> 01:58:06,800
There was also...

1135
01:58:06,800 --> 01:58:12,800
There were some other efforts where Mississippians went to Washington to protest

1136
01:58:12,800 --> 01:58:14,800
and met with the federal agencies.

1137
01:58:14,800 --> 01:58:16,800
I think that's kind of where I got the idea from.

1138
01:58:16,800 --> 01:58:18,800
That was in the summer.

1139
01:58:18,800 --> 01:58:20,800
I mean, that was in January of 65.

1140
01:58:20,800 --> 01:58:28,800
I think people went to DC and met with all these federal agencies about the way the programs were being delivered in the South.

1141
01:58:28,800 --> 01:58:31,800
And...

1142
01:58:31,800 --> 01:58:34,800
Anyway, yeah, so there was...

1143
01:58:34,800 --> 01:58:36,800
I had a certain level of privilege.

1144
01:58:36,800 --> 01:58:38,800
I had that education privilege and the white privilege.

1145
01:58:38,800 --> 01:58:40,800
I had a car at that point.

1146
01:58:40,800 --> 01:58:46,800
It was also partly my parents able to, you know, fund a car.

1147
01:58:46,800 --> 01:58:50,800
It wasn't a new car, but it was, you know, it got me from place to place.

1148
01:58:50,800 --> 01:58:53,800
So there was a level of privilege there.

1149
01:58:53,800 --> 01:59:01,800
And there was also a level of the freedom within SNCC to kind of figure out what you could do within your...

1150
01:59:01,800 --> 01:59:06,800
What you were interested in that would also ductail with the fight for freedom.

1151
01:59:06,800 --> 01:59:08,800
So, you know...

1152
01:59:08,800 --> 01:59:10,800
And I know that it happened in the...

1153
01:59:10,800 --> 01:59:13,800
In the context, as you said, SNCC's mixing all this soul searching.

1154
01:59:13,800 --> 01:59:14,800
Yes.

1155
01:59:14,800 --> 01:59:15,800
And then there was...

1156
01:59:15,800 --> 01:59:16,800
Exactly.

1157
01:59:16,800 --> 01:59:20,800
And one of the big debates going on is what should the structure of SNCC look like?

1158
01:59:20,800 --> 01:59:21,800
Exactly.

1159
01:59:21,800 --> 01:59:22,800
And versus...

1160
01:59:22,800 --> 01:59:23,800
Or non-structured.

1161
01:59:23,800 --> 01:59:24,800
Right.

1162
01:59:24,800 --> 01:59:28,800
And I was in the structure of faction, interestingly enough, right?

1163
01:59:28,800 --> 01:59:31,800
That we needed a strong central structure because...

1164
01:59:31,800 --> 01:59:39,800
Partly because I had heard from all the field staff that they needed some regularity to the way they were funded.

1165
01:59:39,800 --> 01:59:43,800
And that there was a real anger that Mississippi was getting all this attention and money.

1166
01:59:43,800 --> 01:59:44,800
And they...

1167
01:59:44,800 --> 01:59:50,800
In Georgia, in Alabama, in Arkansas, they were feeling like they were stepchildren of the organization.

1168
01:59:51,800 --> 01:59:54,800
And we're not being funded at the same level.

1169
01:59:54,800 --> 01:59:59,800
And because all the volunteers flooded into Mississippi, then those volunteers had access to money.

1170
01:59:59,800 --> 02:00:03,800
And they went back home and they raised money for the project that they had been part of.

1171
02:00:03,800 --> 02:00:07,800
So, they would send it to McComb or they would send it to...

1172
02:00:07,800 --> 02:00:08,800
It'd be...

1173
02:00:08,800 --> 02:00:12,800
Or they would send it to Greenville or wherever they had been stationed.

1174
02:00:12,800 --> 02:00:13,800
And...

1175
02:00:13,800 --> 02:00:15,800
Or India, Nola, or Ruleville or whatever.

1176
02:00:15,800 --> 02:00:16,800
So, those...

1177
02:00:16,800 --> 02:00:17,800
I don't know which...

1178
02:00:17,800 --> 02:00:25,800
And again, this story has never been written about how those funding inequities played out within the organization,

1179
02:00:25,800 --> 02:00:30,800
how people cope with that and or how comfortable people felt with that.

1180
02:00:30,800 --> 02:00:32,800
So...

1181
02:00:32,800 --> 02:00:33,800
Did you...

1182
02:00:33,800 --> 02:00:37,800
One of the snake paintings that sort of influences the wavelength meeting?

1183
02:00:37,800 --> 02:00:39,800
There were two wavelength meetings.

1184
02:00:39,800 --> 02:00:43,800
So, are you talking about Fall of 65 or Spring of 66?

1185
02:00:43,800 --> 02:00:46,800
It was actually Fall of 64.

1186
02:00:46,800 --> 02:00:49,800
Oh, well, yes, of course, Fall of 64, yes.

1187
02:00:49,800 --> 02:00:53,800
Yes, well, that was the meeting where all the papers were written and presented.

1188
02:00:53,800 --> 02:01:01,800
So, there were papers on every topic on the people, on the...

1189
02:01:01,800 --> 02:01:08,800
You know, there was this kind of attention around the level of education that people had and whether people from the field,

1190
02:01:08,800 --> 02:01:13,800
not the field secretaries, but the sharecroppers that we were working with,

1191
02:01:13,800 --> 02:01:18,800
how key was their voice and how much...

1192
02:01:18,800 --> 02:01:21,800
How important it was to have respect for them.

1193
02:01:21,800 --> 02:01:27,800
So, there was that whole question of education and wisdom.

1194
02:01:27,800 --> 02:01:32,800
And, you know, clearly a lot of stick-step felt there was incredible wisdom in the local people.

1195
02:01:32,800 --> 02:01:34,800
I felt that clearly.

1196
02:01:34,800 --> 02:01:37,800
I mean, they could just take an issue and kind of, you know,

1197
02:01:37,800 --> 02:01:46,800
crystallize it in a very plain, simple language and move people to action, you know.

1198
02:01:46,800 --> 02:01:52,800
So, there were papers about structure, there were papers about culture and creativity,

1199
02:01:52,800 --> 02:01:55,800
there were papers about...

1200
02:01:55,800 --> 02:01:56,800
Oh, my goodness.

1201
02:01:56,800 --> 02:02:01,800
About things like the Freedom Democratic Party or some kind of electoral campaigns,

1202
02:02:01,800 --> 02:02:06,800
there were papers on everything and everybody was encouraged to write a paper if they wanted to.

1203
02:02:06,800 --> 02:02:10,800
And so, that was all put into the mix and the discussion.

1204
02:02:10,800 --> 02:02:16,800
And one of the papers that's gotten a lot of attention over the years is the position paper on women,

1205
02:02:16,800 --> 02:02:17,800
exactly.

1206
02:02:17,800 --> 02:02:19,800
The conversation was published anonymously.

1207
02:02:19,800 --> 02:02:20,800
Exactly.

1208
02:02:20,800 --> 02:02:24,800
But very quickly identified with Mary King and Jesus.

1209
02:02:24,800 --> 02:02:29,800
I know you know about that, but did you or you were working at the time?

1210
02:02:29,800 --> 02:02:30,800
I don't think so.

1211
02:02:30,800 --> 02:02:31,800
I don't think...

1212
02:02:31,800 --> 02:02:35,800
I mean, I'm pretty sure that they may have given it to me or shown it to me.

1213
02:02:35,800 --> 02:02:39,800
But I wasn't in that space at that time at all.

1214
02:02:39,800 --> 02:02:44,800
I wasn't in the women's liberation space until the early 70s.

1215
02:02:44,800 --> 02:02:47,800
And there's, you know, a whole history to that.

1216
02:02:47,800 --> 02:02:51,800
But, yeah, I wasn't in that space.

1217
02:02:51,800 --> 02:02:57,800
So, if they did show it to me and asked me to be what I thought or to be part of it,

1218
02:02:57,800 --> 02:02:59,800
I was not interested.

1219
02:02:59,800 --> 02:03:04,800
And I don't actually remember the debate happening at the way we're meeting.

1220
02:03:04,800 --> 02:03:10,800
So, I don't know whether I wasn't there or whether it's just something that I wasn't interested in.

1221
02:03:10,800 --> 02:03:13,800
And I don't really remember.

1222
02:03:13,800 --> 02:03:22,800
I mean, partly, I think it's partly the background is that I felt so respected and so free to do,

1223
02:03:22,800 --> 02:03:31,800
to be in the moment, to be in the struggle to make a contribution that I didn't see this discriminatory,

1224
02:03:31,800 --> 02:03:36,800
you know, making women to feel be felt less than.

1225
02:03:36,800 --> 02:03:44,800
In fact, even though I come out of a tradition where women are not respected and honored and whatever,

1226
02:03:44,800 --> 02:03:47,800
but I felt that SNCC did give me that affirmation.

1227
02:03:47,800 --> 02:03:51,800
And so, I didn't need to fight for women's liberation for saying,

1228
02:03:51,800 --> 02:03:56,800
because I think also I felt the freedom struggle was paramount.

1229
02:03:56,800 --> 02:04:04,800
So, it's interesting. At some point I want to go back and read all of the discussions about the women's movement during the abolitionist time

1230
02:04:04,800 --> 02:04:12,800
and find out what the different women's positions were on why they did or didn't join the separate women's organizations,

1231
02:04:12,800 --> 02:04:18,800
and why they felt that their struggle should be subservient to the Black Freedom struggle.

1232
02:04:18,800 --> 02:04:21,800
Because that's kind of how I felt, I think.

1233
02:04:21,800 --> 02:04:28,800
And again, you know, looking back, I can see that the struggle of Black women was clearly,

1234
02:04:28,800 --> 02:04:41,800
should have been lifted up more than it was, or could have been, I mean, certainly the position of Black women was much more challenging than that of Black men.

1235
02:04:41,800 --> 02:04:47,800
And then the White Women's Movement left the Black Women out of their equation for many decades,

1236
02:04:47,800 --> 02:04:56,800
in fact, probably still does on some level. But somehow, I guess I thought that the Black struggle was the dominant struggle,

1237
02:04:56,800 --> 02:05:03,800
and therefore I was not going to be diverted by this women's liberation thing.

1238
02:05:03,800 --> 02:05:09,800
And I don't know if it was because I thought I would, you know, I thought I would, somebody would call me a traitor,

1239
02:05:09,800 --> 02:05:16,800
or they would, you know, it was too self-centered, or I don't remember what it was, or why it was.

1240
02:05:16,800 --> 02:05:19,800
Okay.

1241
02:05:19,800 --> 02:05:32,800
I think you've probably already answered this, but I know Mary, King, and Casey Hayden talk about, you know, sharing books about, you know, women's issues,

1242
02:05:32,800 --> 02:05:37,800
and having these discussions, it sounds a little bit like what you were doing in graduate school.

1243
02:05:37,800 --> 02:05:38,800
Exactly.

1244
02:05:38,800 --> 02:05:39,800
Yeah.

1245
02:05:39,800 --> 02:05:43,800
Were you, do you remember that part of that network at all?

1246
02:05:43,800 --> 02:05:50,800
I wasn't, I don't remember. I mean, like the Simone de Beauvoir, and who's the Doris Lessing books.

1247
02:05:50,800 --> 02:05:58,800
I remember reading Doris Lessing later, once I was in DC, but I don't, I wasn't part of that.

1248
02:05:58,800 --> 02:06:04,800
You know, I was just in the trenches doing the work, you know, whatever had to be stuff in the envelopes,

1249
02:06:04,800 --> 02:06:11,800
writing the stuff to be sent out to raise the money, right? I was just so focused on all of that.

1250
02:06:11,800 --> 02:06:20,800
So you mentioned that you and Mary and Barry were looking at the education materials, and when you wrote that report.

1251
02:06:20,800 --> 02:06:30,800
I know SNCC opens a DC office, initially as a support office, and in general, and then there was the DC-MFTP office.

1252
02:06:30,800 --> 02:06:31,800
Exactly.

1253
02:06:31,800 --> 02:06:38,800
And part of that is connected to the strong Howard University non-violent action group.

1254
02:06:38,800 --> 02:06:46,800
But at a certain point, SNCC starts moving towards working in DC, organizing DC in its own right.

1255
02:06:46,800 --> 02:06:47,800
Yes.

1256
02:06:47,800 --> 02:06:49,800
Can you talk about that, or jealous?

1257
02:06:49,800 --> 02:06:59,800
A little bit. Well, a little bit. I mean, I think it mostly happened after I left, but we did the, we, I, so at some point,

1258
02:06:59,800 --> 02:07:08,800
I make this transition from the, the federal programs person to working full time in the DC office.

1259
02:07:08,800 --> 02:07:14,800
I'm not quite sure if that happens in November or December. I have an apartment in DC by then.

1260
02:07:14,800 --> 02:07:18,800
I guess I'm just full time DC office.

1261
02:07:18,800 --> 02:07:24,800
So when you, sorry, when you first started working on federal programs, are you still based out of Atlanta?

1262
02:07:24,800 --> 02:07:32,800
Yes. I'm based out of Atlanta. I'm traveling to Arkansas to Alabama. I never went to Southwest Georgia in that process.

1263
02:07:32,800 --> 02:07:42,800
But, and then I go to DC, and I stay in, there was a freedom house in Mount Pleasant in DC at the time, or somebody lived there. I just stayed there temporarily.

1264
02:07:42,800 --> 02:07:47,800
But by December, I think I have an apartment in DC on California Street. And so on...

1265
02:07:47,800 --> 02:07:49,800
This would be like December 65.

1266
02:07:49,800 --> 02:07:59,800
Yes. So on permanently a part of the Washington Snick Office. So in January, February of 65, there are two initiatives that happen.

1267
02:07:59,800 --> 02:08:08,800
One is a 3DC movement, which has to do with the fact that the District of Columbia doesn't have voting representation in Congress.

1268
02:08:08,800 --> 02:08:18,800
And so we have a logo that has a chain, and there are hands pulling the chain apart. It's 3DC is the logo.

1269
02:08:18,800 --> 02:08:27,800
And a guy named LD Pratt comes from Kansas, or Iowa, or somewhere, an older white guy, and Maryann, and he become very chummy.

1270
02:08:27,800 --> 02:08:34,800
And this kind of drives a wedge in the office, too, because he's much older than all the rest of us, right?

1271
02:08:34,800 --> 02:08:44,800
And Maryann Barry, who's the head of the Washington Snick Office, he becomes very chummy with him. And so the staff, we're kind of feeling a little bit left out of the decision-making process.

1272
02:08:44,800 --> 02:08:57,800
But one of the things that they concoct is an approach to big businesses, department stores, that kind of thing, in DC, and ask them to put this logo in their window that says 3DC.

1273
02:08:57,800 --> 02:09:09,800
And I forget if they were supposed to give us some money, or what they were supposed to do. But if you didn't put the logo in your window, then you were told, well, we were going to boycott you.

1274
02:09:09,800 --> 02:09:24,800
Now, I don't think Snick actually boycotted anybody. I don't remember, but I remember the big department stores would would in low-thruppin' and heck company, and so on, were some of the targets to get this 3DC decal in the window.

1275
02:09:24,800 --> 02:09:29,800
And I don't know if anybody's written this history up either. This would be interesting history, right?

1276
02:09:29,800 --> 02:09:43,800
So, and Marion, of course, has passed away, so he can't share. There's a couple of people, Tina Smith, who's still in DC, who might have some of this history because she worked kind of as the administrator in the Washington office.

1277
02:09:43,800 --> 02:09:54,800
Eric Jones is somebody else, who's a Snick person who worked in the Washington office, who's still in DC, comes to the Snick meetings and reunions.

1278
02:09:54,800 --> 02:10:04,800
So, anyway, that was one thrust. The other thrust we did was a bus boycott, and that would have been in February or March of 66.

1279
02:10:04,800 --> 02:10:22,800
And let me ask, so while you're doing these thrusts in DC, there must still be an FTP office that's working on the congressional challenge, because that was January in 1965, though, wasn't it?

1280
02:10:22,800 --> 02:10:32,800
So, this is a year later. I think the MFP office may be as closed. I don't really know, at this point. I know there were Charlene Crants could give you the dates of that.

1281
02:10:32,800 --> 02:10:42,800
But Marion, so we start this bus boycott, and I think it was around bus fares. I think the issue was bus fares.

1282
02:10:42,800 --> 02:10:53,800
We had this very clever plan where we would give people rides to work, and we used Benning Road as the big thoroughfare that we concentrated on.

1283
02:10:53,800 --> 02:11:06,800
And we had, in the basement of the Snick office, which was at On Road Island Avenue, we had this array of telephones that was supposed to take the incoming calls from people.

1284
02:11:06,800 --> 02:11:20,800
And I think it only lasted a few days. I don't know if we even won the fair stabilization. It's very murky in my mind, but I do know that right after that, I quit.

1285
02:11:20,800 --> 02:11:36,800
I wrote a letter talking about how the internal culture in the Snick office was not an atmosphere where people could be participatory, could participate in the decision making process, which is what it had been.

1286
02:11:36,800 --> 02:11:40,800
And it was time for me to move on. So I did.

1287
02:11:40,800 --> 02:11:50,800
Can you talk about what the racial dynamics were in the organization? You come to Snick in fall 64.

1288
02:11:50,800 --> 02:11:53,800
In March of 64. That's okay. No problem.

1289
02:11:53,800 --> 02:12:00,800
In March of 64, and Atlanta. And at that point, it's very much an interracial office.

1290
02:12:00,800 --> 02:12:09,800
Exactly. It's mostly African American, though. It's never predominantly white. Even in the Atlanta office. It's not predominantly white.

1291
02:12:09,800 --> 02:12:17,800
If I ticked off the names of the people, you wouldn't be predominantly white.

1292
02:12:17,800 --> 02:12:30,800
So yes, but it is an interracial office. And there are some situations where there are interracial relationships. And there are some living situations which are interrelational.

1293
02:12:30,800 --> 02:12:42,800
Interracial. But there are also some situations where black staff live together. And I don't remember. Maybe it's the fall of 65.

1294
02:12:42,800 --> 02:12:50,800
No, I'm sorry. The fall of 64, there are some parties which are black-only parties. And I'm only vaguely aware.

1295
02:12:50,800 --> 02:12:57,800
I'm kind of like one of these people who is not totally tuned in to have all the different social dynamics.

1296
02:12:57,800 --> 02:13:04,800
So I'm kind of only vaguely aware. And I'm not feeling like I'm left out. I'm not feeling that this is some horrible thing.

1297
02:13:04,800 --> 02:13:13,800
Black people want to have a party. Have a party. So I'm not paying too much attention.

1298
02:13:13,800 --> 02:13:26,800
I do know there was a lot of controversy around people who had interracial relationships, especially Foreman, who was in an interracial relationship and who had an African American wife.

1299
02:13:26,800 --> 02:13:40,800
So there was a lot of tension around that. I'm thinking that I'm becoming aware of the racism that I carry, the prejudice, the stereotypes that I carry with me.

1300
02:13:40,800 --> 02:13:55,800
But nobody is really there schooling me. As I think today, there are a lot of white people who are able to school other white people on the nature of privilege, on our, the way we perpetrate microaggressions,

1301
02:13:55,800 --> 02:14:13,800
the way that we are insensitive and don't understand. Like somebody told me a story last night about a church, Sunday school, where a woman was talking about planting flowers and taking a bulb and talking about how the bulb was brown and ugly.

1302
02:14:13,800 --> 02:14:29,800
And this woman actually had two vibrational daughters in the Sunday school class. And she was like brown and ugly. You know, are my kids going to, you know, be feeling less than since brown is associated with ugly.

1303
02:14:29,800 --> 02:14:42,800
And so she will speak to that person. But the person probably had no clue, wasn't doing it for any malicious reason. But nobody schooled us on that stuff.

1304
02:14:42,800 --> 02:14:55,800
You know, nobody talked to us about hair or about, you know, about the stereotypes or the ways in which we were, we were not appreciative of what the black community was.

1305
02:14:55,800 --> 02:15:10,800
And I word for years that I was not appreciative of the, of the, of both the resources that I was able to. Like I stayed in somebody's house during the summer of 64 and I was given the only bedroom.

1306
02:15:10,800 --> 02:15:23,800
I mean, what's that about? You know, it's like, and I feel angry at myself for not being much more connected to that privilege and insisting that the couple moved back into their own bedroom and I sleep on the couch.

1307
02:15:23,800 --> 02:15:39,800
But that wasn't what they were imagining because they were welcoming us. So those kinds of things, I think we weren't, there was just nobody that was schooling us on, on how to be and what the disconnect between our upbringing and the upbringing.

1308
02:15:39,800 --> 02:15:57,800
Or the, or the, the poverty of the South and the, the more a's of the South, nobody was able to guide us. I don't think I don't remember anybody guiding us. So, you know, so I think the black only parties or the tensions were part of that.

1309
02:15:57,800 --> 02:16:22,800
And of course, you know, later on I realized that part of that was that we were the closest as, as your consciousness about racial oppression, as a, as a black person, as your consciousness about racial oppression intensifies and you peel back the layers and you see what the, what the incredible brutality is and the incredible denial of rights.

1310
02:16:22,800 --> 02:16:51,800
We're the white people, we're the closest white people to them. So no wonder their anger and their fury is somehow directed at us, even though we're not the culprits, we're not the perpetrators of the, of the oppression, but we're, we're there. We're, we're right there. We're the symbol of, of white supremacy in within this Nick organization. So, you know, in fact, in DC, a kid, this was in 68, I think after Dr. King was killed.

1311
02:16:51,800 --> 02:17:20,800
I'm walking down 18th street and a black kid comes up and hits me in the face and he says, you dirty white lady or something like that, right? And I'm like, taken aback, but then I'm thinking, well, okay, you know, this is part of what the color of racial oppression is like in the country. It's not, and I couldn't take it personally. I mean, I knew that I had, you know, that I was playing a different role than the white oppressor, but, but it's still stung, you know, because it's not like that.

1312
02:17:20,800 --> 02:17:32,800
It's stung, you know, because I got a kid was pissed off at me, right? And so it pushes you into a space where you recognize what that white power control supremacy is all about.

1313
02:17:32,800 --> 02:17:46,800
Do you have any sense of how much that's because it would, would the tension have been the same if he hadn't been married to a black woman at the time?

1314
02:17:46,800 --> 02:17:59,800
It could have been, I mean, one of the things at Wavelin, at one of the Wavelin meetings, and I'm forgetting whether it was fall of 64, spring of 65, there was a whole thing about backsliding.

1315
02:17:59,800 --> 02:18:08,800
And it was black men who had white partners or white relationships. Now, I was in a relationship with Mary and Barry.

1316
02:18:08,800 --> 02:18:29,800
So he was part of that conversation stokely, I think, had had relationships with white women. So there were the whole conversation about these black men who had white, white relationships or white, you know, white, maybe not partners in the traditional sense, because these relationships didn't last very long, right?

1317
02:18:29,800 --> 02:18:45,800
Because we were young, so we went from one person to another. But there was lots of conversation about, you know, and I think this is, again, as the nationalist movement was building and as the frustrations of the US not changing, the country not changing.

1318
02:18:45,800 --> 02:18:55,800
And of us being young and not understanding that the struggle was long and that it wasn't going to happen overnight. I mean, both black and white, young people, we didn't get that, you know.

1319
02:18:55,800 --> 02:19:03,800
We thought we were like going to really transform the country. And boy, it didn't happen the way we imagined it.

1320
02:19:03,800 --> 02:19:15,800
What's your memory of when SNCC starts talking about whites working in the white community? How did you respond to that?

1321
02:19:15,800 --> 02:19:36,800
Well, I think that I probably was not, well, okay, let me back up. I think that there was some talk about that in certainly in Mississippi, there was some talk about going into the white community during the election in fall of 64, to kind of, you know, with, I don't know whether we had Lyndon B. Johnson signs or what the deal, I didn't do it.

1322
02:19:36,800 --> 02:19:50,800
But there were a number of white people who went into the white community, but who got pretty much harassed by the police, rejected by the local white population, kind of told it get out of town, you're a nigger lover, or type of thing.

1323
02:19:50,800 --> 02:19:59,800
So that initiative was not very, that initiative was not, didn't last very long.

1324
02:19:59,800 --> 02:20:17,800
The other thing that was happening, there was a Southern Student Organizing Committee, or SOC, which was Southern white students who did go on white campuses to try to find sympathetic white students who would support the civil rights organizing or the freedom movement.

1325
02:20:17,800 --> 02:20:23,800
So there was that. I think there were a bunch of reasons why we didn't go into the white community.

1326
02:20:23,800 --> 02:20:33,800
One is, well, okay, one is because I don't think we felt any connection to the white working class folks that we might have been canvassing.

1327
02:20:33,800 --> 02:20:40,800
And I guess we didn't imagine that we were going to be talking to white businessmen or white legislators or people like that.

1328
02:20:40,800 --> 02:20:51,800
We imagine we would go door knocking in a neighborhood or canvassing in a neighborhood and would be working with class folks and we just felt no, you know, here we were a middle class, northerners educated.

1329
02:20:51,800 --> 02:21:03,800
Right? So I think we just, it was, we didn't feel the connection. That was one. Another is that we, here we were in this incredible community of civil rights workers.

1330
02:21:03,800 --> 02:21:18,800
And we felt very passionate about our community, very close to everybody, very, like we had died and gone to heaven because we were in this incredible community of struggle and of change and of power.

1331
02:21:18,800 --> 02:21:34,800
Because it was a very powerful community in the term, in the sense that we were, that we were, you know, our mission was to transform the country, to make it the country that we had been taught, it was the kind of country we had been taught it was when we were kids, you know.

1332
02:21:34,800 --> 02:21:44,800
And that was separate from anybody of color. That was like, these are the ideals of the country, democracy, freedom, et cetera.

1333
02:21:44,800 --> 02:21:57,800
And that was another reason we felt close to this community. Another reason I think is we didn't think politically we were going to change these folks. I think we didn't understand how we could change.

1334
02:21:57,800 --> 02:22:05,800
So we imagined it was the clan and us, you know, so it was white people were in the clan or they were clan sympathizers and us.

1335
02:22:05,800 --> 02:22:24,800
And so we didn't, again, go into the white community. There was never any conversation also of when we went back home going into the white community at home and, and getting people to be more committed or I mean we did say yes, organize money when you go back home and organize at federal buildings and that kind of thing.

1336
02:22:24,800 --> 02:22:37,800
But there was never any thinking about intentionally going into the white community to winning people over who who were not in that space of being supportive of the freedom movement.

1337
02:22:37,800 --> 02:22:52,800
Now today one of the things I'm involved in is showing up for racial justice, which is a national organization of white people calling white people into the multiracial America, calling white people into stand for racial justice.

1338
02:22:52,800 --> 02:23:21,800
And it feels like I'm fulfilling that snake promise of going to the white community and organize by being connected to this amazing national network of white people who are working in the white community, calling people in to work for racial justice, calling people in to understand the inequities, the inequitable structures in the country to understand white privilege in a way that, you know, white people are not going to be able to be in the white community.

1339
02:23:21,800 --> 02:23:30,800
You know white people mostly don't think about it or talk about it. And it's it's it's very, very exciting, I think.

1340
02:23:30,800 --> 02:23:33,800
What's the connection between that and the black lives you're married?

1341
02:23:33,800 --> 02:23:46,800
Well, okay, so showing up for racial justice was formed in 2009 when the attacks began on Obama and a number of people of color led organizations said, well where are the white people standing up against these attacks?

1342
02:23:46,800 --> 02:23:59,800
And I think for white progressives, maybe we were totally in love with Obama. We didn't really, you know, we didn't buy the yes we can, the deeper aspects that we wanted out of yes we can.

1343
02:23:59,800 --> 02:24:15,800
So anyway, a lot of these white folks who had been doing anti-racist organizing and training and work said, oh yeah, good point. We got to stand up against this. And so the first organization was called US, no room for racism.

1344
02:24:15,800 --> 02:24:28,800
The US for all of us is what it was called. And there were, I won't go into the whole history, but, but is that's a whole other set of interviews for somebody to do at some point.

1345
02:24:28,800 --> 02:24:40,800
But by the time that Trayvon Martin was killed by George Zimmerman, there was a lot of work had been done about how do we dismantle white supremacy structures, what, what does it mean?

1346
02:24:40,800 --> 02:24:57,800
And so there was a toolkit that was done put online on showing up for racial justice's page about how to organize around the murder of Trayvon Martin and what were the themes, what were the things that people could be doing, what action they could be taken.

1347
02:24:57,800 --> 02:25:05,800
And then when my brown was killed in Ferguson in August of 2014, the chapter structure just began to mushroom.

1348
02:25:05,800 --> 02:25:15,800
So that was kind of the inception of it, but then because the Black Lives Matter movement propelled people's thinking and consciousness much further forward.

1349
02:25:15,800 --> 02:25:33,800
And I think the Michelle Alexander work around the New Jim Crow and the impact of the criminal justice system, the mass incarceration and the over-policing of black communities, all that understanding, which was done by some amazing scholars, and then popularized around the country.

1350
02:25:33,800 --> 02:25:43,800
And then the murders that were lifted up by cell phone video, etc. Then the showing up for racial justice nationally works with the Black Lives Matter movement.

1351
02:25:43,800 --> 02:26:02,800
They have accountability relationships. And so one of the things about Surge, that's the nickname for showing up for racial justice, is to work in conjunction with Black Lives Matter organizations with local black led and people of color led organizations that are putting forward the vision.

1352
02:26:02,800 --> 02:26:11,800
So that's the vision for how we move to a more equitable structure, structures and how we change the country.

1353
02:26:11,800 --> 02:26:14,800
What is some of the work you've been doing with Surge here in Baltimore?

1354
02:26:14,800 --> 02:26:28,800
Well, in April when the Baltimore uprising happened, I was asked by the National Coordinator of Surge, who actually is somebody I had known from my organizing days in the 90s and the 2000s.

1355
02:26:28,800 --> 02:26:45,800
And she asked if I could find some people who would talk about the Baltimore background. So I got two women of color who spoke on a conference call of 700 people just after the uprising, right, about the Baltimore background, what led to it, what the circumstances were.

1356
02:26:45,800 --> 02:27:09,800
And then in that call was the time where the St. Louis people had been doing door knocking with Black Lives Matter signs. And then the people in Arizona had been doing door knocking with signs saying no on SB 1070, which was the law that criminalized immigrants that Sheriff Arpaio had been doing in Arizona.

1357
02:27:09,800 --> 02:27:23,800
I mean, he shackled immigrants and brought them to the public square in Phoenix, like they were just common criminals shackled them and had them walking around in like orange jumpsuits. I mean, the images are just incredible.

1358
02:27:23,800 --> 02:27:33,800
This is pretty Trump, right. I mean, this is, but, but anyway, so, I lost my turn.

1359
02:27:33,800 --> 02:27:51,800
So that we learned about the door knocking that had happened in St. Louis and that had happened in Arizona on that call. And then the charge was take a selfie of yourself saying I support the Baltimore uprising or with the hashtag Baltimore uprising, which is a Twitter handle, I guess, I'm not on Twitter.

1360
02:27:51,800 --> 02:28:06,800
And then go out and doorknock with Black Lives Matter signs talk to people, go into white neighborhoods and talk to people about structural inequity and about racism and police brutality and that kind of thing.

1361
02:28:06,800 --> 02:28:21,800
So I began to, I got an organization that I was in locally called Baltimore Racial Justice Action to agree to, to do the door knocking with the signs and you see the sign in my yard. And I have a sign here. You want to take a picture of it later.

1362
02:28:21,800 --> 02:28:45,800
So we did that. We did the door knocking and then I was asked by showing up for racial justice if I wanted to become a regional resource person. And I agreed. And so I went to Highlander in August, which was very exciting because I had never been in Highlander Highlander Education Center. I never went there during civil rights move because I wasn't important enough to go there.

1363
02:28:45,800 --> 02:28:50,800
So, people don't know Highlander, can you say something about their role as a movement?

1364
02:28:50,800 --> 02:29:06,800
Sure. So, yes. So they actually began in the 30s and they began with tobacco workers and textile workers and they brought black and white workers together from the South to talk about their common purpose and their common struggle.

1365
02:29:06,800 --> 02:29:26,800
And then when the pre-the-siddings, I think they were already doing the September Clark for example and Rosa Parks went to Highlander to talk about citizen education and talk about organizing across the South. So they played a big role in bringing white and black activists together in the South.

1366
02:29:26,800 --> 02:29:44,800
They, Miles Horton, who was the director of Highlander, did a lot of popular education teaching. So it was a way to go into areas where people were unorganized and used popular education techniques to have people discuss their situation.

1367
02:29:44,800 --> 02:30:05,800
The A.K.A. Paolo Ferry, who was a Brazilian popular educator, to do this process of consciousness raising. So Highlander was kind of a core place. They got bombed. They had to move from where they were in Tennessee to another place because they were bombed and their lease was taken from them.

1368
02:30:05,800 --> 02:30:15,800
This is all in the either late 50s or early 60s so they moved to and now they're in a particular place where they own the land and they're pretty stable.

1369
02:30:15,800 --> 02:30:25,800
I know they were shut down by the state of Tennessee, but they were bombed.

1370
02:30:25,800 --> 02:30:43,800
I might be wrong. I mean you're the historian of all these. Right, right. Yeah, and maybe they weren't bombed. Maybe that's just my recollection of the way the Southern culture worked that you bombed somebody if you didn't, it weren't in favor of their work.

1371
02:30:43,800 --> 02:30:57,800
So we jumped to your current work with Serge and Paul Timor on racial justice. What can you talk about the intervening years, the 40 years in between?

1372
02:30:57,800 --> 02:31:02,800
Right. Right. Right. Right. Right. Right. You did leaving SNCC. Okay.

1373
02:31:02,800 --> 02:31:06,800
There was so much in being a part of the women's room at a certain point. Yeah.

1374
02:31:06,800 --> 02:31:18,800
Okay, so when I left SNCC, I moved to Washington and I stayed in Washington and I worked in a black community arts program for a number of years.

1375
02:31:18,800 --> 02:31:32,800
And then I got involved in the anti-war movement, which was a big center was in DC. So I, and I, you know, reconnected with some of the SDS people and some of the people who had been a Mississippi were white who were in the anti-war movement.

1376
02:31:32,800 --> 02:31:43,800
So I did some anti-war organizing while I worked in this art center. We did some organizing as white people around the rebellion after Dr. King's death.

1377
02:31:43,800 --> 02:31:56,800
We did some taking supplies into the black community, that kind of thing. We had an organization called the emergency, which was white people talking about race and equity.

1378
02:31:56,800 --> 02:32:07,800
Then I got the women's movement reached me in the early 70s. So I was in a couple of consciousness raising groups. I didn't do a lot with the women's movement.

1379
02:32:07,800 --> 02:32:18,800
But I, you know, I kind of came to my own understanding about women's oppression and how it affected me by being in connection with these amazing women in the liberation movement.

1380
02:32:18,800 --> 02:32:24,800
Then I did change your son's on what you'd experienced and, and snake.

1381
02:32:24,800 --> 02:32:29,800
Can snake or SDS or any of the other work you've done before?

1382
02:32:29,800 --> 02:32:40,800
It probably helped me center it. I mean, helped me realize what I, but I think it, I think it didn't, it didn't say to me, oh my God, you were really oppressed in snake Betty.

1383
02:32:40,800 --> 02:32:52,800
No, it didn't say to me at that at all. It might have said, okay, I wonder why I didn't feel that oppression because I was valued and affirmed and given opportunities that I never would have had otherwise.

1384
02:32:52,800 --> 02:32:58,800
You know, I mean, as Judy Richardson says, if you were, you could do anything you were big enough to do.

1385
02:32:58,800 --> 02:33:19,800
So if you took a step way out there and crafted some idea for what you could do or if you, you know, if you thought of a new, like in my case, I was doing the Northern Support Work, if I thought of some new initiative that I could do in that context, I could do it and be affirmed to doing it.

1386
02:33:20,800 --> 02:33:30,800
Yeah, no, so then I moved, I mean, there were some other things that I did in there, but I eventually I moved to Baltimore in 1972 to work in a factory.

1387
02:33:30,800 --> 02:33:37,800
And that was part of young people across the country feeling that the country hadn't changed sufficiently enough.

1388
02:33:37,800 --> 02:33:47,800
And so we went to work in factories to get the work in class involved in some kind of, you know, radical transformative process for the US.

1389
02:33:47,800 --> 02:33:53,800
So I worked in this factory for eight years. I married a factory worker, a black factory worker.

1390
02:33:53,800 --> 02:34:13,800
I left the factory when one of my daughters had a birth defect and I needed to not be fired from my job, but I got a fabulous job working for a doctor who was an occupational medicine doctor who got a grant from HRSA, which is the,

1391
02:34:14,800 --> 02:34:25,800
it's a government agency, HRSA, it's in high-end spill. Anyway, he got a grant to teach medical students about occupational medicine.

1392
02:34:25,800 --> 02:34:31,800
And part of it was taking medical students to factories on factory tours.

1393
02:34:31,800 --> 02:34:42,800
And so I did that for three years. I took medical students to all of the factories in Baltimore to Bethlehem Steel, to the Chevrolet plant, to the glass plant where I had one of the places I had worked.

1394
02:34:42,800 --> 02:34:58,800
To the, our coast steel to a bunch of different places. And then Reagan was elected in the meantime, and he pulled the plug on these grants.

1395
02:34:58,800 --> 02:35:14,800
So then I worked for the same doctor in an asbestos screening program where we saw building trades workers who had been exposed to asbestos and of course had asbestosis or cancer from their asbestos exposure.

1396
02:35:14,800 --> 02:35:23,800
So I kind of deepened all that understanding about the public health of factory work or industrial work or working class occupations.

1397
02:35:23,800 --> 02:35:41,800
And then because Reagan had pulled the plug on this grant and then I lost the funding. So I went to work at Hopkins, Johns Hopkins in the School of Public Health. And I worked for 14 years in different, I worked in injury prevention and I worked in HIV and AIDS research.

1398
02:35:41,800 --> 02:36:01,800
And then the organizing bug just was growing in me. So in 1997, I had been asked to come to this conference at Evergreen College in the summer of, or the spring of 1997.

1399
02:36:01,800 --> 02:36:21,800
It must have been 1995 and it was the initial conference of this of a group called the National Organizers Alliance, which brought organizers together across the country to think about what kind of things were needed and necessary and what work was going on.

1400
02:36:21,800 --> 02:36:36,800
So I went and I was on a fishbowl about SNCC and with some other people with Hardy Fry from Berkeley with Mike Miller, with I think Jerome Scott was on that fishbowl, but he had been in the black workers organizing and Detroit.

1401
02:36:36,800 --> 02:36:50,800
But anyway, so I did that and it's in the that I'm reading about organizing and learning about what's going on around the country and so the bug is really getting a hold of me.

1402
02:36:50,800 --> 02:37:04,800
So in 97, I'm calling Baltimore organizations to see if they want to send somebody to this conference in Colorado, which was all another gathering of the National Organizers Alliance.

1403
02:37:04,800 --> 02:37:15,800
And the, this woman is telling me who works for Citizens Planning and Housing Association to the local nonprofit doing housing work and anti crime work in Baltimore.

1404
02:37:15,800 --> 02:37:22,800
Working in all the neighborhoods where the wire was actually filmed and interestingly enough.

1405
02:37:22,800 --> 02:37:30,800
So she says to me, well, we don't have anybody to send to the conference, but do you know somebody who knows organizing who could be our lead organizer?

1406
02:37:30,800 --> 02:37:35,800
And I'm like, oh my gosh, I'm going to apply for this job and I actually got the job.

1407
02:37:35,800 --> 02:37:45,800
I mean, I think I got it partly because I knew how to supervise people from my time at Hopkins and partly because of my history and what I, what I have been through.

1408
02:37:45,800 --> 02:37:52,800
So I worked there for eight years and worked in, it was neighborhood organizing.

1409
02:37:52,800 --> 02:38:04,800
And then I had an OSI fellowship to do, to bring organizers together across open society institute fellowship to bring organizers together across issues and constituencies.

1410
02:38:04,800 --> 02:38:09,800
I did that. Then by then I'm like almost 65, not quite.

1411
02:38:09,800 --> 02:38:15,800
And then so then I did a variety of different, well, when I, when my fellowship ended, I was 65.

1412
02:38:15,800 --> 02:38:22,800
So I've done a number of different organizing jobs. I work for a union. I work for a parent organizing group.

1413
02:38:22,800 --> 02:38:39,800
I did some consulting on writing curriculum for community colleges on organizing so we could grow the number of organizers of color in the country because a lot of the organizers, the professional organizers, and I'm putting quotes around professional white.

1414
02:38:39,800 --> 02:38:50,800
And then from the big faith based networks, those were mostly white organizers and very often the nonprofits were hiring white people to go and organize even if they were organizing in the black community.

1415
02:38:50,800 --> 02:39:00,800
So I worked on this curriculum for a couple of years and yeah, that led me to showing up for racial justice.

1416
02:39:00,800 --> 02:39:02,800
So that's my current work.

1417
02:39:02,800 --> 02:39:14,800
So the things from the civil rights movement, the modern movement that was our 60s movement that you think are important that we haven't talked about?

1418
02:39:14,800 --> 02:39:22,800
I think we've pretty much covered it. I think we've pretty much covered it. I mean, if you, if you gave me a prompt, I might say, oh yeah, we left that out.

1419
02:39:22,800 --> 02:39:25,800
Yeah, I can't think of anything off the top of my head.

1420
02:39:25,800 --> 02:39:34,800
But do you think are important for people to know about the civil rights movement and organizing for social and racial justice?

1421
02:39:34,800 --> 02:39:45,800
I think people need to know what a movement is and what the window, what the energy level is during a movement, which we're certainly in a movement time now.

1422
02:39:45,800 --> 02:39:51,800
And what the window is, however, because the window doesn't last that long.

1423
02:39:51,800 --> 02:40:02,800
So the work that we have to do, the strategic thinking that we have to apply, we do need to go fast, but we also need to go slow to go fast.

1424
02:40:02,800 --> 02:40:06,800
And, you know, we can't like move so fast.

1425
02:40:06,800 --> 02:40:28,800
I mean, white culture says, you move fast, you get it done type of thing. But really that's, if we're in a moment of accountability, this way I'm thinking about it, we're in a moment of accountability, and we're in accountability with the Black Lives Matter movement, we can't go so fast that we move out ahead of where people are developing.

1426
02:40:28,800 --> 02:40:38,800
And I think the form of the Black Lives Matter movement is going to be very different from the civil rights movement. The issues are similar but different.

1427
02:40:38,800 --> 02:40:47,800
And the energy is definitely very similar in the thinking and the depth of commitment is very similar.

1428
02:40:47,800 --> 02:41:01,800
I think it's important for people to know that movements need resources and that white community has lots of resources and we should be making a commitment to using some of our resources for sustaining Black Lives Matter organizations.

1429
02:41:01,800 --> 02:41:19,800
For example, I do a monthly sustainer for showing up for racial justice and I also have a monthly sustainer to the Baltimore Algebra Project, which is young people creating space for young people to, they tutor other young people in math, but they also do some organizing.

1430
02:41:19,800 --> 02:41:35,800
And I also have a monthly sustainer with 1DC, which is organizing neighborhood equity in DC, which is a really strong organization in Washington that organizes in the Black community, anti-gentrification organizing, that kind of thing.

1431
02:41:35,800 --> 02:41:46,800
So yeah, I think resources are important. I think scholarship is important. I think it's fabulous that there's been so much scholarship done of the 60s movement.

1432
02:41:46,800 --> 02:41:56,800
And that we have young scholars like Emily Crosby and Hassan Jeffries and others who have written these powerful books and lifted up the history.

1433
02:41:56,800 --> 02:42:04,800
I think reading is important. I mean, you know, I despair at the fact that young people don't read anymore, right?

1434
02:42:04,800 --> 02:42:12,800
And they kind of get these blips from the internet, but they don't read and study and process the history.

1435
02:42:12,800 --> 02:42:22,800
So I think history, we have to lift up history and the importance of history. And I love it that the Library of Congress is doing these interviews.

1436
02:42:22,800 --> 02:42:33,800
What else? Yeah, I think we're in a different moment now because we have global capital and we have this level of exploitation that's unseen.

1437
02:42:33,800 --> 02:43:02,800
And that is obscene. So I think we have to be really thinking about the whole anti-war. How do we connect the sense of the Black Lives Matter movement with the anti-war organizing, with all the other human rights organizing, certainly with the identity politics of the gender, the gender non-conforming movement?

1438
02:43:02,800 --> 02:43:31,800
I don't know if that's a movement yet, but the whole conversation about gender non-conforming structures. But how do we mesh all of that? And for me, the Black movement is the center because I think because the country was birthed in such an exploitive relationship to the enslaved population and to slavery as the basis of the US wealth.

1439
02:43:31,800 --> 02:43:43,800
And I think that that has to be the straw that has to be where we focus our energy in order to open up all the other transformative processes and potential in the country.

1440
02:43:43,800 --> 02:43:45,800
So, thank you.

1441
02:43:45,800 --> 02:43:52,800
Yeah, you're welcome. It was a pleasure to chat with the Library of Congress.

1442
02:43:52,800 --> 02:44:02,800
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

